# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avocado
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avocado/agouti] The **agouti** (/əˈɡuːtiː/ ⓘ, *ə-GOO-tee*) or **common agouti** is any of several rodent species of the genus ***Dasyprocta***, from Ancient Greek δασύς (*dasús*), meaning "hair", and πρωκτός (*prōktós*), meaning "anus".
[src:avocado/agouti] They are native to Central America, northern and central South America, and the southern Lesser Antilles.
[src:avocado/agouti] Some species have also been introduced elsewhere in the West Indies and in west Africa (Bénin).
[src:avocado/agouti] They are related to guinea pigs and look quite similar, but they are larger and have longer legs.
[src:avocado/agouti] The species vary considerably in colour, being brown, reddish, dull orange, greyish, or blackish, but typically with lighter underparts.
[src:avocado/agouti] Their bodies are covered with coarse hair, which is raised when alarmed.
[src:avocado/agouti] The related pacas were formerly included in genus *Agouti*, but these animals were reclassified in 1998 as genus *Cuniculus*.
[src:avocado/agouti] The Spanish term is *agutí.* In Mexico, the agouti is called the **sereque**.
[src:avocado/agouti] In Panama, it is known as the **ñeque** and in eastern Ecuador, as the **guatusa**.
[src:avocado/agouti] The name "agouti" is derived from either Guarani or Tupi, both South American indigenous languages, in which the name is written as *akuti*.
[src:avocado/agouti] The Portuguese term for these animals, *cutia*, is derived from this original naming.
[src:avocado/agouti] Agoutis have five toes on their front feet and three toes on their hind feet; the first toe is very small.
[src:avocado/agouti] The tail is very short or nonexistent and hairless.
[src:avocado/agouti] The molar teeth have cylindrical crowns, with several islands and a single lateral fold of enamel.
[src:avocado/agouti] Agoutis may grow to be up to 60 cm (24 in) in length and 4 kg (8.8 lb) in weight.
[src:avocado/agouti] Most species are brown on their backs and whitish or buff on their bellies; the fur may have a glossy appearance and then glimmers in an orange colour.
[src:avocado/agouti] Reports differ as to whether they are diurnal or nocturnal animals.
[src:avocado/agouti] In the wild, they are shy animals and flee from humans, while in captivity they may become trusting.
[src:avocado/agouti] In Trinidad, they are renowned for being very fast runners, able to keep hunting dogs occupied with chasing them for hours.
[src:avocado/agouti] Agoutis are found in forested and wooded areas in Central and South America.
[src:avocado/agouti] Their habitats include rainforests, savannas, and cultivated fields.
[src:avocado/agouti] They conceal themselves at night in hollow tree trunks or in burrows among roots.
[src:avocado/agouti] Active and graceful in their movements, their pace is either a kind of trot or a series of springs following one another so rapidly as to look like a gallop.
[src:avocado/agouti] They take readily to water, in which they swim well.
[src:avocado/agouti] When feeding, agoutis sit on their hind legs and hold food between their forepaws.
[src:avocado/agouti] They may gather in groups of up to 100 to feed.
[src:avocado/agouti] They eat fallen fruit, leaves and roots, although they may sometimes climb trees to eat green fruit.
[src:avocado/agouti] They hoard food in small, buried stores.
[src:avocado/agouti] They sometimes eat the eggs of ground-nesting birds and even shellfish on the seashore.
[src:avocado/agouti] They may cause damage to sugarcane and banana plantations.
[src:avocado/agouti] They are regarded as one of the few species (along with macaws) that can open Brazil nuts without tools, mainly thanks to their strength and exceptionally sharp teeth.
[src:avocado/agouti] In southern Brazil, their main source of energy is the nut of *Araucaria angustifolia*.
[src:avocado/agouti] Agoutis give birth to litters of two to four young (pups) after a gestation period of three months.
[src:avocado/agouti] Some species have two litters a year in May and October, while others breed year round.
[src:avocado/agouti] The pups are born in burrows lined with leaves, roots and hair.
[src:avocado/agouti] They are well developed at birth and may be up and eating within an hour.
[src:avocado/agouti] Fathers are barred from the nest while the young are very small, but the parents pair bond for the rest of their lives.
[src:avocado/agouti] They can live for as long as 20 years, a remarkably long time for a rodent.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Agricultural Experiment Station established in 1921 developed into the Agricultural Research Organization (ARO), widely known as the Volcani Institute.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Faculty of Agriculture of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, Tel Aviv University, Bar Ilan University, Ben Gurion University of the Negev and the Weizmann Institute of Science also engage in agricultural research.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Farming has been practiced in the region which became Israel for 10,000 years.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In the late 19th century Jewish and Palestinian Arab farmers expanded the acreage devoted to commercial and export crops.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The forerunners of agricultural research in Palestine were the teachers and instructors of the Mikveh Israel agricultural school, established in 1870.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The pioneers of many of the early farming settlements cultivated experimental plots supervised by an agronomist.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Arriving in the country with little or no previous agricultural experience, this kind of experimentation was vital for the development of such crops as grapes, citrus and almonds.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Arab agriculture revolved primarily around dry farming, with wheat, barley, chickpeas, sesame and olives predominating.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The few German Templer villages were based on relatively large farms of dry farming of wheat and barley.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1906, Jewish agronomist Aaron Aaronsohn discovered wild emmer (*Triticum dicoccoides*), believed to be "the mother of the wheat.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] After the Balfour declaration by Great Britain in 1917 and the award of the mandate to Palestine by the League of Nations to Britain, the Jewish Agency established in 1921 the Agricultural Experiment Station.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Their mission was to conduct research leading to small farms with intensive agriculture, specializing in mixed farming of fruit trees, cattle, chicken, vegetables and cereals.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The research station, headed by Yitzhak Elazari Volcani and located in Rehovot, was the first scientific institute in Palestine.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] It had departments for crop sciences, fruit and citrus, soil and irrigation, entomology and plant pathology, post-harvest, food technology and farm economics.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The station had an extension department and results of its research were quickly passed on to the farmers.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Yields of grain under dryland conditions increased from 600 to 5000 kg per hectare; and breeding and selection of cattle increased milk production from 800–1500 kg to 5000 kg/cow/year (1950) {now more than 11.000 kg/cow/year- 2005}.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Research in storage of citrus fruit reduced spoilage during shipping to Europe due to fungal rots from 30% to 2-3%.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1942 the Hebrew University in Jerusalem decided to establish the Institute for Agricultural Studies, which later developed into the Faculty of Agricultural, Food and Environmental Quality Sciences.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In the beginning the faculty staff came mainly from the Agricultural Experiment Station and students worked on their theses in the laboratories of the Station.Michael Evenari (1904-1989, born as Walter Schwarz) was among the early pioneers.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The British government also established a small agricultural research department with several stations in both Arab and Jewish areas.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] After 1948, with the establishment of the State of Israel, the two research stations were merged into the Agricultural Research Station within the Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] However, the extension and advisory service, previously part of the research station, now became an independent branch within the Ministry.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The modern brand cherry tomato was developed by Israeli scientists in the 1970s.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1960 an attempt was made to merge the Agricultural Research Station with the Faculty of Agriculture of the Hebrew University, to form the "National and University Institute of Agriculture." The idea was based on the US model of the Land Grant Colleges).
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] This attempt failed, mainly because the basic working conditions were not equalized before the merger.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Nevertheless, a close cooperation exists between the two institutions.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The senior researchers of the Agricultural Research Station serve on the teaching staff of the Faculty and students from the Faculty do their research for M.Sc. and Ph.D. theses at the Research Station.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] With the growth of the various disciplines in the Agricultural Research Station and the establishment of regional research stations, the organizational structure has changed over time.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Agricultural Research Organization (ARO) was established in 1971, incorporating all agricultural research within the Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Within the ARO are six institutes, two commodity (Plant and Animal Sciences) and four discipline oriented institutes (Plant Protection, Soil, Water and Environmental Sciences, Technology & Storage of Agricultural Products and Agricultural Engineering).
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The ARO has two additional research centers – Gilat, in southern Israel and Neve Ya'ar in the north.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Within the six institutes the various scientific departments cover all agricultural disciplines except veterinary sciences.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In addition to the Institutes the ARO maintains a computer unit, Genomics and Bio-informatics section, technology transfer (engaged in business related activities), international activities, youth activity units and a library.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Veterinary Institute of the Veterinary Services of the Ministry of Agriculture is also located on the central campus of the ARO.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] These goals require development of new products and cultivars, improvement of food quality and safety, functional food, integrated pest management (IPM), precision agriculture and farming efficiency, with agricultural technologies friendly to the environment.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The fund of the Chief Scientist is open to scientists from all institutions – ARO, universities, regional research organizations, extension specialists and farmers.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In addition to the Chief Scientist's fund the various commodity branches, as vegetables, flowers, fruits, dairy cattle etc. also allocate research funding of direct interest to them.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Minister of Agriculture, upon recommendation of the Chief Scientist, appoints the committee members for research in each commodity branch.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In general a third of the members come from the scientific community, a third from the extension service and a third are farmers.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The proposals submitted to the commodity branches also undergo the scientific evaluation process.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] A substantial source of funding, mainly for more basic research, comes from bi-national funds.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The leading one is The United States - Israel Binational Agricultural Research and Development Fund (BARD).
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] BARD is a competitive funding program for mutually beneficial, mission-oriented, strategic and applied research of agricultural problems, jointly conducted by American and Israeli scientists.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Since 1979, BARD has funded over 870 research projects, with awards of about $9.5 million annually for new research projects.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Most of these are of three years duration, the average award being $300,00.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Budgets are distributed about equally between the two countries.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Proposals are evaluated both in the US by the Agricultural Research Service (ARS) and in Israel by the Scientific Evaluation Committees (SEC), based on expert reviewers from different countries.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The recommendations from ARS and SEC are brought before a Technical Advisory Committee (TAC) for final recommendations to the Board of BARD.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The success of BARD led to the establishment of additional bi-national funds as the Joint Dutch-Israeli Agricultural Science and Technology Program, a bi-national Program with Queensland (Australia) and Canada.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The latter are all on a much lower funding level than BARD.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In addition funding is also obtained from the EU, The US – Israel Bi-national Science Foundation (BSF) and others.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Faculty of Agriculture, Food and Environmental Quality Sciences of the Hebrew University in Rehovot is a major partner in the conduct of agricultural research.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In the Faculty, which includes Agricultural economics and management, a School of nutritional sciences and hotel, food and tourism management are about 90 tenured scientific staff.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The major scientific disciplines are: Agricultural Botany; Field Crops, Vegetables and Genetics; and Horticulture; Biochemistry, Food Science and Nutrition; Entomology and Plant pathology; Soil and water sciences; Animal sciences; Veterinary medicine and Agricultural economics and management.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Additional research is carried out at Bar-Ilan University, Tel Aviv University, the Weizmann Institute of Science, and Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, whose Jacob Blaustein Institute specializes in arid-zone agriculture.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The ARO and its forerunner, the Agricultural Research Station, have helped to turn Israel's “mixed farming” system into a highly industrialized enterprise focused on export to Europe.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Serious water shortages have led to the use of low quality and recycled water.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Some 44% of the water used for agriculture comes from recycled water without lowering quality of the produce.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Exports to Europe include fruits (citrus, avocado, grapes), vegetables (sweet peppers, tomatoes, potato, melons, sweet potato), ornamentals (cut flowers, potted plants, propagation material) and herbs.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 1997, agricultural export (fresh and processed) reached over $1.329 billion - approximately 6.4% of the country's total exports (Source: Central Bureau of Statistics).
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] This has necessitated an ongoing search for new products, niches in seasons and better storage technologies.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Major achievements included an increase in productivity of fruit, vegetable and field crops with a reduced input of chemical fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] Efficiency in dairy farming has increased milk production to one of the highest in the world: over 10,200 litre/cow/year.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 2010, Jonathan Gressel of the Weizmann Institute received the Israel Prize for agricultural research.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The prize committee chose Gressel, who is internationally known for his work in plant biotechnology, for breakthrough research in molecular structures that has major implications for the development of weed killers.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] The Israel Prize for Agriculture was previously awarded to about 10 different scientists mainly from the Agricultural Research Organization (previously the Agricultural Experiment Station) and the Faculty of Agriculture of the Hebrew University among them Prof.
[src:avocado/agricultural-research-in-israel] In 2012, Daniel Hillel received the World Food Prize for his pioneering work in micro-irrigation techniques.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] During the early colonial period, the Spanish introduced more plants and the concept of animal husbandry, principally cattle, horses, donkeys, mules, goats and sheep, and barnyard animals such as chickens and pigs.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Farming from the colonial period until the Mexican Revolution was focused on large private properties.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] After the Revolution, these were broken up and the land redistributed.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Since the latter 20th century NAFTA and economic policies have again favoured large scale commercial agricultural holdings.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico’s main crops include grains such as corn and wheat, tropical fruits and various vegetables.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Agricultural exports are important, especially coffee, tropical fruits and winter fruits and vegetables.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Sixty percent of Mexico’s agricultural exports go to the United States.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The territory of Mexico roughly corresponds with that of Mesoamerica, which was one of the cradles of plant domestication.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Archeological research in the Gulf coast of Tabasco shows the earliest evidence of corn cultivation in Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The first fields were along the Grijalva River delta with fossilized pollen evidence showing forest clearing around 5100 BCE.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The domestication of corn is followed by sunflower seeds and cotton.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Agriculture was the basis of the major Mesoamerican civilizations such as the Olmecs, Mayas and Aztecs, with the principal crops being corn, beans, squash, chili peppers and tomatoes.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The tradition of planting corn, beans and squash together allows the beans to replace the nitrogen that corn depletes from the soil.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The three crops together are sometimes referred to as the Three Sisters.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Soil erosion from corn production has been a problem since the Mesoamerican period.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] This and other kinds of environmental degradation have been cited as the cause of the collapse of the Teotihuacan civilization.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] To create new areas for cultivation, Mesoamericans harvested rainfall, developed lakeshore irrigation systems and created new fields in the form of terraces and "chinampas" artificial floating islands in shallow waters.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Although silver mining brought many Spaniards to Mexico and silver was the largest single export from New Spain, agriculture was extremely important.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] There were far more people working in agriculture, not only producing subsistence crops for individual households and small-scale producers for local markets, but also commercial agriculture on large estates (haciendas) to supply Spanish cities.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In the early conquest period, Spaniards relied on crops produced by indigenous in central Mexico and rendered as tribute, mainly maize, following existing arrangements.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Some Spaniards were awarded grants by the crown of indigenous tribute and labor in the conquest-era institution of encomienda, which was phased out replaced by indigenous labor allocations by the crown (*repartimiento*), finally wage labor or other non-coerced labor arrangements.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In central Mexico, the rise of the Spanish population in and the drop in indigenous population in the sixteenth century saw Spaniards acquiring land, creating haciendas and smaller farms called *ranchos*.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Much productive land was held by indigenous villages, with the protection of the crown, but long-term trend over the colonial era and the nineteenth century was the transfer of those lands into non-indigenous hands.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Hacienda owners (*hacendados*) sought to maximize income and minimize production costs, economically rational behavior.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In Mexico City, chinampa agriculture was highly productive and labor intensive, supplying the capital, with land continuing to be held by indigenous farmers into the twentieth century.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The Spanish introduced a number of new crops such as wheat, barley, sugar, fruits (such as pear, apple, fig, apricot, and bananas) and vegetables, but their main contributions were domesticated animals, unknown in Mesoamerica.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The Spanish brought cattle, horses, goats, and sheep as part of what is now called the Columbian Exchange.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] These animals often caused damage to indigenous crops in central Mexico, but outside the zone of intense indigenous settlement and cultivation, cattle and sheep were grazed on land not previously devoted to agriculture.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Sheep grazed on previously cultivated land had disastrous environmental consequences, documented in a classic of Mexican environmental history.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] With the discovery and exploitation of large-scale silver deposits in Zacatecas and Guanajuato, cultivated areas outside of traditional agriculture expanded, particularly in the Bajío, which became the bread basket of Mexico producing the imported grain, wheat.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Unlike central Mexico, which had a long indigenous tradition of sedentary agriculture, much of the Bajío was a marshy wetland not continuously occupied or cultivated.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] For the Spaniards, the Bajío was a disappointment, since there were no deposits of precious metals and no indigenous populations with existing hierarchies, but the region did show promise for initially the grazing of cattle and later agriculture.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] With population growth in silver mining cities in the eighteenth century, agriculture expanded and cattle grazing was displaced to more marginal lands and declined in importance.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Agriculture in the region was productive, but was not technologically innovative.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The bottom lands were rich in nutrients Spaniards had no sense that access to productive land was restricted, which might have sparked innovation in cultivation.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] However, the shaping of the regions hydrology with dams and canals in the eighteenth century made possible wheat cultivation on a large scale.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Spaniards developed irrigated agriculture, with the construction of canals and dams, marshy land was drained and redirected.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] A number of native plant and animal species from Mexico proved to have commercial value in Europe, leading to their mass cultivation and export including cochineal and indigo (for dyes), cacao, vanilla, henequen (for rope), cotton, and tobacco.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] A high quality, fast red dye from small cochineal insects that were cultivated and collected from the nopal cactuses on which they thrived was an extremely important export to Europe, the second most valuable after silver.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Cochineal production was labor intense and largely remained in indigenous hands.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mesoamerican staple foods, especially maize, continued to be important.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In the eighteenth century, when the Spanish crown was seeking new sources of income, it created a monopoly on tobacco production and processing, restricting cultivation to areas around Orizaba.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Recent assessments of the Roman Catholic Church's role in the Mexican economy have examined the hypothesis that the church was a major drag on the Mexican economy.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Since the church functioned as the main source of credit to elites, its lending to them at below market rates cost the church revenue and increased the wealth of those acquiring the credit.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The church owned considerable land in its own right.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] An advantage of church-owned haciendas over privately held ones was that unlike individual hacendados, whose deaths triggered a division of property among the heirs, the church as a corporation continued to consolidate its wealth over time.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Land tenure and agricultural production continued along the patterns of the colonial era even after the Mexican War of Independence (1810–21).
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Much of the fighting had taken place in the Bajío, Mexico's bread basket, and the silver mines were damaged as well, so there were factors that led to stagnation in agriculture there.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Political turmoil in the post-independence era was an obstacle to economic growth, but agriculture itself did not put a drag on it.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] One economic historian considers Mexico's "pre-capitalist agricultural organisation" one of Mexico's several obstacles to industrial development.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Low rates of economic growth generally were also due to the lack of a national market and high transportation costs.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Most Mexicans were subsistence farmers using rain as the main source of water for their crops.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In the post-independence era, much agricultural land was in the hands of corporate owners, that is the Roman Catholic Church and indigenous communities, and those lands could not be alienated under colonial law and its continuation in the early republic (1822-1855).
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] They could not be rented or used as collateral for potentially more profitable enterprises.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexican liberals targeted corporate ownership of land during the Liberal Reform era, and the landed wealth of the church was expropriated, but much land was still held by indigenous communities.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Political turmoil continued until the last quarter of the nineteenth century with the coup by liberal army general Porfirio Díaz.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Once he had consolidated power, large haciendas were encouraged to develop commercial farming for export, made possible by the building of railroads to take products to market at low freight rates.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Railroads were built using foreign capital and by extending land concessions to the entrepreneurs.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Much indigenous land was usurped and land prices where railway lines were built soared.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Displaced agricultural workers found temporary employment building railway lines.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Indigenous village lands that had largely escaped the Liberal Reform were now expropriated at rapid rates.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Large haciendas became profitable again, reversing a trend toward gradual disintegration into smaller units.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Expropriated church lands remained in the hands of large-scale producers.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Landless indigenous villagers became rural or urban wage laborers.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] When wheat production in the U.S. and Canada expanded in the nineteenth century and mechanized reapers developed, the binding of cut wheat for later threshing opened a market for the commercial development of the henequen industry in Yucatán.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Henequen production on a large scale had never been commercially viable before, but the production of henequen for cordage rapidly became a major export product to the U.S. and Canada.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Cotton production was the fastest growing agricultural sector, with textile factories being established in the states of Puebla and Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Factories produced both cotton yarn and finished textiles.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] With the development of a network of railway lines, commercial agriculture became more generally possible.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Tobacco was an important crop, no longer protected as a colonial monopoly of the crown, and cigarette factories using machine-rolled cigarettes produced 5 million kilos in 1898.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The result was the Mexican Revolution from 1910 to 1920.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The result afterwards was the breakup of most large private landholdings to be redistributed, especially under a system of common tenancy regulated by the government called ejidos.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The lands could be worked individually or collectively by members of the ejido but the land could not be leased or sold.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The process of dividing lands and developing ejido organizations continued into the 1930s under President Lázaro Cárdenas.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] By the end of the 1930s, haciendas almost entirely disappeared from central and southern Mexico with numerous small holdings of ten to twenty acres as well as ejidos becoming dominant.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Land reform in Mexico was an achievement of the Mexican Revolution, with the distribution of land to peasants concentrated in Mexico's center and south.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The breakup of the haciendas solved a political problem in Mexico, since it was one of the demands of the peasants who fought and was enshrined.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] By the 1930s and 40s, agricultural production was dropping and the government sought technical solutions.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Soils in central Mexico were considered exhausted by use and inadequate so that the government promoted agricultural development outside the traditional areas of cultivation, particularly in northern Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In the 1940s during the presidency of Manuel Avila Camacho, the Mexican government partnered with the U.S. government, and the Rockefeller Foundation to launch the so-called Green Revolution (1950–70).
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Research facilities developed new strains of wheat, maize, beans, and other crops, to engineer a variety of desirable traits, such as disease resistance, high protein content.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Sorghum, a new crop was introduced to Mexico during the era of the Green Revolution, which was used for animal fodder.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico expanded cattle production in this era, fed on sorghum.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Seeds and inputs of fertilizer and pesticides for irrigated agriculture were suited to Mexico's northwest, but required more capital than small-scale cultivators could afford.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Synthetic fertilizers required adequate water so that its nitrogen would not be toxic to crops.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The application of both pesticides and fertilizers were applied regularly.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Pemex, Mexican national oil company, and Fertimex, the national company for the production of pesticides, particularly DDT, were integral in promoting large-scale, agribusiness dependent on these synthetic inputs.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In order to be competitive, Green Revolution crops had to be cultivated and harvested by machinery, which meant that it was economically viable only with large-scale farms.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The ejido system remained intact until the 1990s.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] However, during World War II, industry became the more important sector of the economy.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico’s rural population began to fall in the mid century, from 49.3% in 1960 to 25.4% in 2000.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Federal policies outside ejidos still favored large agricultural producers over rural peasant production, including the offering of credit and protectionist policies.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] One of these was the construction of major irrigation systems, especially in the north.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The first major irrigation project was the Laguna Project near Torreón, followed by the Las Delicias Project near Chihuahua, both with the aim of producing cotton along with wheat.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] These projects increased the amount of land available for agriculture from 3.7 million acres in 1950 to 8.64 million acres in 1965.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In addition, the Mexican government encouraged only crops such as corn and beans, restricting imports of these two staples until 1990.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] By the 1970s, agricultural production was unable to keep up with population growth leading to imports of basic staples.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The Mexican government initiated programs in the 1970s and 80s to encourage family planning and the utilization of birth control, in order to reduce surging population growth.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The peasant population had increased 59% in the period 1940–1960, with the number of work days in the fields going from 190 days in 1950 to 100 days in 1960.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Overpopulation was a factor in internal migration as well as migration for work to the U.S.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The rise of neoliberalism and the negotiation of NAFTA in the early 1990s pushed agriculture towards even more commercialized enterprises.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The Mexican constitution was modified in 1992 to allow for leasing and selling of ejido land if the majority of members voted in favor.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The goal of this was to allow ejidos to combine to form larger and more efficient farms, with money invested from private sources, but has resulted in most ejido land becoming privately held.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] These changes have had uneven effects on Mexican agriculture.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Until the late 1990s, Mexico was a net exporter of agricultural products, but today it is a net importer, mostly from the United States.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] With the need to compete with imported grains and less direct support from the government, the agricultural sector entered a crisis.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexican agricultural income has polarized with large commercial farms dominating the sector and at the other end small subsistence farming which still is the main source of income for many, especially in the south of the country.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The former are able to take advantage of reduced trade barriers and exports, especially to the United States have increased.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Former subsidies provided by the government was replaced by a program called Procampo, which gave direct cash payments to farmers growing corn, beans, wheat and other grains, allowing farmers to decide what to plant.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Despite greater output, agriculture continues to decrease in percentage of Mexico’s GDP since 1990.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The proportion of GDP of agriculture, forestry and fishing fell from 8% of the nation’s GDP in 1990 to 5.4% of Mexico’s GDP in 2006, with a growth rate of only 1.6% during that time, far behind other sectors of the economy.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In 2010, the structure of the GDP and labor force showed agriculture, forestry, and fishing combined was valued at 3.8% of total value, employing 5,903,300 or 12.5% of the labor force.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Commercial agricultural products mostly come from three areas of the country, the tropics of the Gulf of Mexico and Chiapas Highlands, the irrigated lands of the north and northwest and the Bajío region in central Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] At the beginning of the 21st century Mexico’s main agricultural products include beef, fruits, vegetables, corn, milk, poultry, pork and eggs, which make up about 80% of agricultural production.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The most profitable tropical crops are coffee and sugarcane.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Coffee is exported but sugarcane is mostly for domestic consumption.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Other important tropical crops are fruits such as bananas, pineapples and mangos as well as cacao and rice.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Vanilla is still also grown, which is native to Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Cotton is an important crop in the export agricultural areas of the Soconusco in Chiapas and in the north of Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] As of the early 21st century, the rural workforce is still significant but it is shrinking.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Traditional farming methods with small plots worked by families and small communities still dominate in many regions especially those with large indigenous populations such as the Southern Plateau.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In these areas the main crops are corn, beans and squash as in the Mesoamerican period.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Many farmers still survive on subsistence agriculture earning cash by selling excess crops in local markets, especially in central and southern Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Export of agricultural products to the United States is particularly important, especially since the implementation of NAFTA.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] While only about twelve percent of United States agricultural exports go to Mexico, about sixty percent of Mexico agricultural exports go to the United States.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico’s growing population has made the country a net importer of grains.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Under NAFTA, the US has an advantage in the production of corn but Mexico has the advantage in the production of vegetables, fruits and beverages.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The two fastest growing exports to the US are winter fruits and vegetables as well as fruit juices and fresh flowers.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Two important products for export to the United States are avocados and tomatoes.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The US prohibited import of Mexican avocados for over eighty years for hygienic reasons.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In 1997, began to allow import of avocados from Michoacán.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Most of the imported tomatoes eaten in the United States now come from Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Significant Mexican agribusiness enterprises include Grupo Maseca, headquartered in Monterrey.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] It has modernized corn flour production in Mexico and is the largest corn flour producer in the United States.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Pulsar International in Monterrery has a number of high-tec agribusiness concerns including Savia, which has operations in 123 countries.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] A number of U.S. agribusiness enterprises have significant investments in Mexico, including Campbell Soup, General Mills, Ralston Purina and Pilgrim’s Pride.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The last is the second largest poultry producer in Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] New grain initiatives of President Andrés Manuel López Obrador have reduced subsidies to middle and large producers with the objective of increasing smaller scale production for national consumption.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico has a territory of 198 million hectares of which fifteen percent is dedicated to agricultural crops and fifty eight percent which is used for livestock production.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Much of the country is too arid and/or too mountainous for crops or grazing.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Forests cover 67 million hectares or thirty four percent of the country.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The terrain of Mexico consists of two large plateaus (Northern and Southern), the Sierra Madre Oriental and Sierra Madre Occidental mountain chains and narrow coastal plains.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] These make for a wide variety of ecosystems, most of them dry due to the fact that most moisture comes from the Gulf of Mexico with the north–south mountain chains blocking much of this flow, especially in the north where it is almost entirely arid or semi arid.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The wettest areas of the country are those along the Gulf of Mexico coast.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The climate and topography limits agricultural production to 20.6 million hectares or 10.5% of the nation’s territory.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Twenty five percent of this land must be irrigated.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] About half of the territory or 98 million hectares is used for grazing including natural grassland, various scrublands, tropical forests and conifer-oak forests.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] About 75% of grazing land is in northern Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Sixty five percent of soils in Mexico are shallow and with low yield for crops.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] There are eleven main soil types in Mexico, mostly determined by climate patterns.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] These are the Northwest, the Gulf of California, the Central Pacific, the North, the Centre, the Northeast, the Gulf of Mexico, the Balsas-Oaxaca Valley, the South Pacific, the Southeast and the Yucatán.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Those with high potential cover about twenty six percent of the country and are already heavily exploited.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The greatest variety of soils is in the Centre and the Gulf of Mexico, areas with the highest population densities.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] It is estimated that no more than one-fifth of the territory can be made to be arable.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] About one fifth of Mexico’s fields are irrigated, which is crucial for commercial production in arid north and northwest Mexico with cotton as the most important irrigated crop.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Underground aquifers have been under depletion at rates higher than one meter per year in most regions, with the raising of alfalfa one reason.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Ownership of agricultural land in Mexico is either private or in some form of collective tenure, most often in an ejido arrangement.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Ejidos were created in the first half of the 20th century to give Mexican peasants rights over redistributed lands, but this did not include leasing or selling.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In 1992, the Mexican constitution was amended to modify this arrangement.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] However, most commonly held lands such as ejidos are characterized by small plots worked by families which are not efficient nor qualify for financial products such as loans.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The growing of crops is the most important aspect of Mexico’s agriculture, accounting for fifty percent of agricultural output.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Main crops include corn, sugarcane, sorghum, wheat, tomatoes, bananas, chili peppers, oranges, lemons, limes, mangos, other tropical fruits, beans, barley, avocados, blue agave and coffee.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The most important crops for national consumption are wheat, beans, corn and sorghum.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The most important export crops are sugar, coffee, fruits and vegetables, most of which are exported to the United States.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The most important animal feed crop is alfalfa followed by sorghum and corn.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Corn is still the most important crop in Mexico, grown on almost sixty percent of its cropland and contributing to just over nine percent of human calorie intake and fourteen percent of protein intake.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Central Mexico grows about sixty percent of the country’s corn, almost exclusively in the rainy season from June to October.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] While self-sufficient in the production for human consumption, half of Mexico’s grain imports are for feed corn for animals.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Many of these crops are important regionally.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Wheat is the most important crop in the northwest, now the center of Mexico’s grain production.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Other important crops in the northwest are winter vegetables such as tomatoes and lettuce as well as oilseeds.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The traditional area for grain production in Mexico was the Bajío region.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The region still produces wheat, corn, vegetables, peanuts, strawberries and beans, mostly on small holdings.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Wine grapes are grown in areas such as Baja California, Coahuila and Querétaro.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico produces two crops not generally produced elsewhere, henequen used to produce a strong fiber and maguey, both in the agave family.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Maguey is used for the making of pulque as well as mezcal.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Tequila is a type of mezcal made from the blue agave in a designated zone mostly in Jalisco.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The production of some important export crops, such as avocados from the state of Michoacan, have been the target of drug cartels that extort producers.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Livestock accounts for thirty percent of Mexico’s agricultural output, producing milk, poultry, eggs and beef.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Mexico is not self-sufficient in the production of meat and fish, importing its remaining needs mainly from the United States.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The north of Mexico has been the most important overall ranching area since the Mexican War of Independence.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Large haciendas often exceeding 385 square miles in size were created in the 1800s and many large holdings survived the reforms associated with the Mexican Revolution.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In the north open-range methods are giving way to rotational grazing systems, with some natural pastures enhanced by means of irrigation, top-seeding and fertilization.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The ruminant section has traditionally been dominated by cattle, which provide 95% of the value of ruminant products.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Thirty percent are raised in the north, 26% raised in central Mexico and 44% raised in the south.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] European breeds for meat such as Hereford, Angus and Charolais are dominant in the north, a local breed called criollo (descendants of those brought over by the Spanish) in central Mexico and Zebu breeds dominant in the south.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Dairy cattle are varieties of Holstein and criollos, 42% raised in the north, 48% in central Mexico and 10% in the south.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Since the 1990s, the raising of cattle, especially for dairy, has grown, mostly in the center and north of Mexico, displacing other kinds of agricultural production.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] After cows are goats, with 20% raised in the north, 58% in Central Mexico and 22% in the south.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Most of these goats are criollos, descendants of those the Spanish brought with Nubian, Alpino and Saanen breeds being introduced.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Seventy five percent of dairy goats are raised in Coahuila, Durango and Guanajuato.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] About two thirds of meat production is on eight states in various parts of Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Following goats are sheep with 16% raised in the north, 60% in central Mexico and 24% in the south.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] Criollo and Rambouillet are dominant in the north, with Suffolk and Hampshire dominating since their introduction in the 1970s in central Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In southern Mexico breeds for tropical areas such as Pelibuey, Black-belly and Katahdin increasingly dominate.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] As natural pasture is not enough to support modern commercial livestock production, animal feed is produced as a crop or as a measure to enhance natural pastures.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] The former has increased since the 1990s and latter has increased more recently with government encouragement, especially in central and northern Mexico.
[src:avocado/agriculture-in-mexico] In many areas, land used for the production of animal fodder, such as sorghum, is replacing that used for the growing of corn for human consumption.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] An **allergy** is an exaggerated immune response where the body mistakenly identifies an ordinarily harmless allergen as a threat.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic reactions give rise to **allergic diseases** such as hay fever, allergic conjunctivitis, allergic asthma, atopic dermatitis, food allergies, and anaphylaxis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Symptoms of allergic diseases may include red eyes, an itchy rash, sneezing, coughing, a runny nose, shortness of breath, or swelling.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Common allergens include pollen, certain foods, metals, insect stings, medications, and materials, such as latex.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The development of allergies is due to genetic and environmental factors.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The mechanism of allergic reactions involves immunoglobulin E antibodies (IgE) binding to an allergen and then to a receptor on mast cells or basophils, where they trigger the release of inflammatory chemicals such as histamine.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Diagnosis is typically based on a person's medical history.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Further testing of the skin or blood may be useful in certain cases.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Positive tests, however, may not necessarily mean there is a significant allergy to the substance in question.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Early exposure of children to potential allergens may be protective.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Treatments for allergies include avoidance of known allergens and the use of medications such as steroids and antihistamines.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In severe reactions, injectable adrenaline (epinephrine) is recommended.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergen immunotherapy, which gradually exposes people to larger and larger amounts of allergen, is useful for some types of allergies such as hay fever and reactions to insect bites.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In the developed world, about 20% of people are affected by allergic rhinitis, food allergy affects 10% of adults and 8% of children, and about 20% have or have had atopic dermatitis at some point in time.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Depending on the country, about 1–18% of people have asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Anaphylaxis occurs in between 0.05–2% of people.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Rates of many allergic diseases appear to be increasing.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The word "allergy" was first used by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Many allergens, such as dust or pollen, are airborne particles.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In these cases, symptoms arise in areas exposed to air, such as the eyes, nose, and lungs.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] For instance, allergic rhinitis, also known as hay fever, irritates the nose, sneezing, itching, and redness of the eyes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Inhaled allergens can also lead to increased production of mucus in the lungs, shortness of breath, coughing, and wheezing.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic rhinitis can simultaneously occur with other allergic responses such as asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Aside from these ambient allergens, allergic reactions can result from foods, insect stings, and reactions to medications like aspirin and antibiotics such as penicillin.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Symptoms of food allergy include abdominal pain, bloating, vomiting, diarrhea, itchy skin, and hives.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Food allergies rarely cause respiratory (asthmatic) reactions, or rhinitis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Insect stings, food, antibiotics, and certain medicines may produce a systemic allergic response that is also called anaphylaxis; multiple organ systems can be affected, including the digestive system, the respiratory system, and the circulatory system.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Depending on the severity, anaphylaxis can include skin reactions, bronchoconstriction, swelling, low blood pressure, coma, and death.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This type of reaction can be triggered suddenly or have a delayed onset.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The anaphylactic reaction may seem to subside, but may recur over time.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Substances that come into contact with the skin, such as latex, are also common causes of allergic reactions, known as contact dermatitis or eczema.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Skin allergies frequently cause rashes, or swelling and inflammation within the skin, in what is known as a "wheal and flare" reaction characteristic of hives and angioedema.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] With insect stings, a large local reaction may occur as an area of skin redness greater than 10 cm in size that can last one to two days.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This reaction may also occur after immunotherapy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The skin forms an effective barrier to the entry of most allergens, but this barrier cannot withstand everything.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] For example, an insect sting can breach the barrier and inject allergen into the affected spot.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] When an allergen enters the epidermis or dermis, it triggers a localized allergic reaction which activates the mast cells in the skin resulting in an immediate increase in permeability of blood vessels, leading to fluid leakage and swelling in the affected area.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Mast-cell activation also stimulates a skin lesion called the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Then the release of chemicals from local nerve endings by a nerve axon reflex causes the widening of surrounding cutaneous blood vessels, which causes redness of the surrounding skin.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] As part of the allergic response, the body has developed a secondary response that, in some individuals, causes a more widespread and sustained skin swelling.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This usually occurs about 8 hours after the allergen originally comes in contact with the skin.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] When an allergen is ingested, a dispersed form of wheal-and-flare reaction, known as urticaria or hives, will appear when the allergen enters the bloodstream and eventually reaches the skin.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This same skin reactivity allows allergists to test for existing allergies by injecting a small amount of an allergen into the skin, which causes a reaction at the injection site.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Even though these injections are very small and local, they still pose the risk of causing systemic anaphylaxis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Substances that come into contact with the airways may trigger allergic reactions in the nose, sinuses, throat and lungs.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic rhinitis, often referred to as hay fever, is one of the most common airway allergies and is characterized by sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching of the nose and eyes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Airborne allergens commonly associated with allergic rhinitis include pollen, house dust mites, animal dander and mold spores.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic reactions involving the lower airways may contribute to allergic asthma, in which exposure to allergens can lead to bronchoconstriction, wheezing, coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, animal allergens and occupational exposures such as flour dust or chemical sensitizers.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some allergic airway reactions may occur rapidly after exposure, while others develop over several hours.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Severe reactions involving airway swelling may impair breathing and constitute a medical emergency.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) is responsible for distinguishing pathogenic organisms from harmless food proteins and commensal bacteria.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Antigens sampled across the intestinal epithelium are presented by CD103+ dendritic cells, which migrate to mesenteric lymph nodes and promote differentiation of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells (Tregs).
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] These Tregs subsequently return to the intestinal lamina propria, where cytokines such as interleukin-10 and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) contribute to the maintenance of immune tolerance and suppression of allergic T helper 2 (Th2) responses.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Disruption of these regulatory pathways may contribute to allergic sensitization and the development of food allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Impairment of the intestinal epithelial barrier, altered antigen processing, inflammation, or reduced regulatory T-cell activity may shift immune responses toward IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Such defects in oral tolerance have been associated with increased Th2 polarization, elevated allergen-specific IgE production, and reduced regulatory immune activity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Environmental and dietary factors, including vitamin D deficiency, infections, antibiotic exposure, and changes in food processing, may also influence allergy development through their effects on gut immunity and epithelial integrity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The intestinal microbiome is increasingly recognized as an important factor in allergy development.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Early-life alterations in the composition and diversity of the intestinal microbiota have been associated with an increased risk of food allergy and atopic disease.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Commensal bacteria contribute to immune maturation, maintenance of epithelial barrier function, and induction of tolerogenic immune responses.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Reduced microbial diversity and loss of certain bacterial taxa may impair oral tolerance and promote allergic sensitization.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Short-chain fatty acids produced by intestinal bacteria may further support regulatory immune pathways and intestinal barrier integrity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Sensitization to food allergens may also occur through non-oral routes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Exposure to allergens through damaged skin, particularly in individuals with impaired skin barriers such as those with atopic dermatitis, may predispose to food allergy if oral tolerance has not yet been established.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This has contributed to the hypothesis that the timing, route, and context of allergen exposure influence whether tolerance or allergic sensitization develops.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Research into gastrointestinal immune mechanisms has influenced preventive approaches to food allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts and eggs, during infancy has been associated in some populations with a reduced risk of food allergy, likely by promoting oral tolerance during critical periods of immune development.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Risk factors for allergies can be placed in two broad categories: host and environmental factors.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Host factors include heredity, sex, race, and age, with heredity being by far the most significant.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] However, there has been a recent increase in the incidence of allergic disorders that cannot be explained by genetic factors alone.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Four major environmental candidates are alterations in exposure to infectious diseases during early childhood, environmental pollution, allergen levels, and dietary changes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Dust mite allergy, also known as house dust allergy, is a sensitization and allergic reaction to the droppings of house dust mites.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The allergy is common and can trigger allergic reactions such as asthma, eczema, or itching.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The mite's gut contains potent digestive enzymes (notably peptidase 1) that persist in their faeces and are major inducers of allergic reactions such as wheezing.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The mite's exoskeleton can also contribute to allergic reactions.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Unlike scabies mites or skin follicle mites, house dust mites do not burrow under the skin and are not parasitic.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Dust mite-proof encasements to mattress, pillow, and duvet prevent chronic contact with allergens.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A wide variety of foods can cause allergic reactions, but 90% of allergic responses to foods are caused by cow's milk, soy, eggs, wheat, peanuts, tree nuts, fish, and shellfish.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Other food allergies, affecting less than 1 person per 10,000 population, may be considered "rare".
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The most common food allergy in the US population is a sensitivity to crustacea.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Although peanut allergies are notorious for their severity, peanut allergies are not the most common food allergy in adults or children.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Other allergens may trigger severe or life-threatening reactions and are more common when combined with asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Rates of allergies differ between adults and children.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Children can sometimes outgrow peanut allergies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Egg allergies affect one to two percent of children but are outgrown by about two-thirds of children by the age of 5.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The sensitivity is usually to proteins in the white, rather than the yolk.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Milk-protein allergies—distinct from lactose intolerance—are most common in children.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Approximately 60% of milk-protein reactions are immunoglobulin E–mediated, with the remaining usually attributable to inflammation of the colon.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some people are unable to tolerate milk from goats or sheep as well as from cows, and many are also unable to tolerate dairy products such as cheese.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Roughly 10% of children with a milk allergy will have a reaction to beef.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Lactose intolerance, a common reaction to milk, is not a form of allergy at all, but due to the absence of an enzyme in the digestive tract.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Those with tree nut allergies may be allergic to one or many tree nuts, including pecans, pistachios, and walnuts.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In addition, seeds, including sesame seeds and poppy seeds, contain oils in which protein is present, which may elicit an allergic reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergens can be transferred from one food to another through genetic engineering; however, genetic modification can also remove allergens.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Little research has been done on the natural variation of allergen concentrations in unmodified crops.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Latex can trigger an IgE-mediated cutaneous, respiratory, and systemic reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The prevalence of latex allergy in the general population is believed to be less than one percent.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In a hospital study, 1 in 800 surgical patients (0.125 percent) reported latex sensitivity, although the sensitivity among healthcare workers is higher, between seven and ten percent.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Researchers attribute this higher level to the exposure of healthcare workers to areas with significant airborne latex allergens, such as operating rooms, intensive-care units, and dental suites.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] These latex-rich environments may sensitize healthcare workers who regularly inhale allergenic proteins.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The most prevalent response to latex is allergic contact dermatitis, a delayed hypersensitivity reaction that manifests as dry, crusted lesions.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This reaction usually lasts 48–96 hours.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Sweating or rubbing the area under the glove aggravates the lesions, possibly leading to ulcerations.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Anaphylactic reactions occur most often in sensitive patients who have been exposed to a surgeon's latex gloves during abdominal surgery, but other mucosal exposures, such as dental procedures, can also produce systemic reactions.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Latex and banana sensitivity may cross-react.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Furthermore, those with latex allergy may also have sensitivities to avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] These people often have perioral itching and local urticaria.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Only occasionally have these food-induced allergies induced systemic responses.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Researchers suspect that the cross-reactivity of latex with banana, avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut occurs because latex proteins are structurally homologous with some other plant proteins.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] About 10% of people report that they are allergic to penicillin; however, of that 10%, 90% turn out not to be.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Serious allergies only occur in about 0.03%.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] One of the main sources of human allergies is insects.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Insect bites, stings, ingestion, and inhalation can trigger an insect allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Another non-food protein reaction, urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, originates after contact with poison ivy, eastern poison oak, western poison oak, or poison sumac.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Urushiol, which is not itself a protein, acts as a hapten and chemically reacts with, binds to, and changes the shape of integral membrane proteins on exposed skin cells.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The immune system does not recognize the affected cells as normal parts of the body, causing a T-cell-mediated immune response.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Of these poisonous plants, sumac is the most virulent.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The resulting dermatological response to the reaction between urushiol and membrane proteins includes redness, swelling, papules, vesicles, blisters, and streaking.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Estimates vary on the fraction of the population that will have an immune system response.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Approximately 25% of the population will have a strong allergic response to urushiol.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In general, approximately 80–90% of adults will develop a rash if they are exposed to 0.0050 mg (7.7×10−5 gr) of purified urushiol.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some people are so sensitive that a molecular trace on the skin can initiate an allergic reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic diseases are strongly familial; identical twins are likely to have the same allergic diseases about 70% of the time; the same allergy occurs about 40% of the time in non-identical twins.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic parents are more likely to have allergic children and those children's allergies are likely to be more severe than those in children of non-allergic parents.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some allergies, however, are not consistent along genealogies; parents who are allergic to peanuts may have children who are allergic to ragweed.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The likelihood of developing allergies is inherited and related to an irregularity in the immune system, but the specific allergen is not.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The risk of allergic sensitization and the development of allergies varies with age, with young children most at risk.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Several studies have shown that IgE levels are highest in childhood and fall rapidly between the ages of 10 and 30 years.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The peak prevalence of hay fever is highest in children and young adults, and the incidence of asthma is highest in children under 10.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Ethnicity may play a role in some allergies; however, racial factors have been difficult to separate from environmental influences and changes due to migration.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It has been suggested that different genetic loci are responsible for asthma, to be specific, in people of European, Hispanic, Asian, and African origins.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some loci, such as PRDM2 and POU2AF1, showed pleiotropic effects linking allergic and autoimmune conditions, suggesting shared inflammatory pathways across epithelial tissues.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Within atopic airway disease specifically, the same review noted that IL-13—produced mainly by activated TH2 cells—is a key driver of eosinophilic airway inflammation and remodeling, acting partly through pathways independent of IgE and eosinophils.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic diseases are caused by inappropriate immunological responses to harmless antigens driven by a TH2-mediated immune response.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Many bacteria and viruses elicit a TH1-mediated immune response, which down-regulates TH2 responses.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The first proposed mechanism of action of the hygiene hypothesis was that insufficient stimulation of the TH1 arm of the immune system leads to an overactive TH2 arm, which in turn leads to allergic disease.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In other words, individuals living in too sterile an environment are not exposed to enough pathogens to keep the immune system busy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Since our bodies evolved to deal with a certain level of such pathogens, when they are not exposed to this level, the immune system will attack harmless antigens.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Thus, normally benign microbial objects—like pollen—will trigger an immune response.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It is used to explain the increase in allergic diseases that have been seen since industrialization, and the higher incidence of allergic diseases in more developed countries.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The hygiene hypothesis has now expanded to include exposure to symbiotic bacteria and parasites as important modulators of immune system development, along with infectious agents.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Epidemiological data support the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Longitudinal studies in the third world demonstrate an increase in immunological disorders as a country grows more affluent and, it is presumed, cleaner.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The use of antibiotics in the first year of life has been linked to asthma and other allergic diseases.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The use of antibacterial cleaning products has also been associated with a higher incidence of asthma, as has birth by caesarean section rather than vaginal birth.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Chronic stress can aggravate allergic conditions.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This has been attributed to a T helper 2 (TH2)-predominant response driven by suppression of interleukin 12 by both the autonomic nervous system and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Stress management in highly susceptible individuals may improve symptoms.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergic diseases are more common in industrialized countries than in countries that are more traditional or agricultural, and there is a higher rate of allergic disease in urban populations versus rural populations, although these differences are becoming less defined.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Historically, the trees planted in urban areas were predominantly male to prevent litter from seeds and fruits, but the high ratio of male trees causes high pollen counts, a phenomenon that horticulturist Tom Ogren has called "botanical sexism".
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Alterations in exposure to microorganisms is another plausible explanation, at present, for the increase in atopic allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Endotoxin exposure reduces release of inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α, IFNγ, interleukin-10, and interleukin-12 from white blood cells (leukocytes) that circulate in the blood.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Certain microbe-sensing proteins, known as Toll-like receptors, found on the surface of cells in the body, are also thought to be involved in these processes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Parasitic worms and similar parasites are present in untreated drinking water in developing countries, and were present in the water of developed countries until the routine chlorination and purification of drinking water supplies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Recent research has shown that some common parasites, such as intestinal worms (e.g., hookworms), secrete chemicals into the gut wall (and, hence, the bloodstream) that suppress the immune system and prevent the body from attacking the parasite.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This gives rise to a new slant on the hygiene hypothesis theory—that co-evolution of humans and parasites has led to an immune system that functions correctly only in the presence of the parasites.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Without them, the immune system becomes unbalanced and oversensitive.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In particular, research suggests that allergies may coincide with the delayed establishment of gut flora in infants.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] However, the research to support this theory is conflicting, with some studies performed in China and Ethiopia showing an increase in allergy in people infected with intestinal worms.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Clinical trials have been initiated to test the effectiveness of helminthic therapy with certain worms in treating some allergies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It may be that the term 'parasite' could turn out to be inappropriate, and in fact a hitherto unsuspected symbiosis is at work.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] These TH2 cells interact with other lymphocytes called B cells, whose role is the production of antibodies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Coupled with signals provided by IL-4, this interaction stimulates the B cell to begin production of a large amount of a particular type of antibody known as IgE.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Secreted IgE circulates in the blood and binds to an IgE-specific receptor (a kind of Fc receptor called FcεRI) on the surface of other kinds of immune cells called mast cells and basophils, which are both involved in the acute inflammatory response.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] At this stage, the IgE-coated cells are sensitized to the allergen.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] If later exposure to the same allergen occurs, the allergen can bind to IgE molecules held on the surface of the mast cells or basophils.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Cross-linking of the IgE and Fc receptors occurs when more than one IgE-receptor complex interacts with the same allergenic molecule and activates the sensitized cell.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This results in rhinorrhea, itchiness, dyspnea, and anaphylaxis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Depending on the individual, allergen, and mode of introduction, the symptoms can be system-wide (classical anaphylaxis) or localized to specific body systems.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Asthma is localized to the respiratory system, and eczema is localized to the dermis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] After the chemical mediators of the acute response subside, late-phase responses can often occur.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This is due to the migration of other leukocytes such as neutrophils, lymphocytes, eosinophils, and macrophages to the initial site.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The reaction is usually seen 2–24 hours after the original reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Cytokines from mast cells may play a role in the persistence of long-term effects.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Late-phase responses in asthma differ slightly from those seen in other allergic responses.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] They are still caused by the release of mediators from eosinophils and remain dependent on TH2 cell activity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Although allergic contact dermatitis is termed an "allergic" reaction (which usually refers to type I hypersensitivity), its pathophysiology involves a reaction that more correctly corresponds to a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In type IV hypersensitivity, there is activation of certain types of T cells (CD8+) that destroy target cells on contact, as well as activated macrophages that produce hydrolytic enzymes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Effective management of allergic diseases relies on the ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergy testing can help confirm or rule out allergies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Correct diagnosis, counseling, and avoidance advice based on valid allergy test results reduce the incidence of symptoms and need for medications, and improve quality of life.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] To assess the presence of allergen-specific IgE antibodies, two different methods can be used: a skin prick test or an allergy blood test.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Both methods are recommended, and they have similar diagnostic value.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Skin prick tests and blood tests are equally cost-effective, and health economic evidence shows that both tests are cost-effective compared with no test.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Early and more accurate diagnoses save costs due to reduced consultations, referrals to secondary care, misdiagnosis, and emergency admissions.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergy undergoes dynamic changes over time.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Regular allergy testing of relevant allergens provides information on if and how patient management can be changed to improve health and quality of life.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Annual testing is often the practice for determining whether allergy to milk, egg, soy, and wheat have been outgrown, and the testing interval is extended to 2–3 years for allergy to peanut, tree nuts, fish, and crustacean shellfish.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Results of follow-up testing can guide decision-making regarding whether and when it is safe to introduce or re-introduce allergenic food into the diet.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Skin testing is also known as "puncture testing" and "prick testing" since it involves a series of tiny punctures or pricks being placed into the patient's skin.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Tiny amounts of suspected allergens and/or their extracts (*e.g.*, pollen, grass, mite proteins, peanut extract) are introduced to sites on the skin marked with pen or dye (the ink/dye should be carefully selected, lest it cause an allergic response itself).
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A negative and positive control are also included for comparison (e.g., negative is saline or glycerin; positive is histamine).
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A small plastic or metal device is used to puncture or prick the skin.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Sometimes, allergens are injected "intradermally" into the patient's skin, with a needle and syringe.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Common areas for testing include the inside of the forearm and the back.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] If the patient is allergic to the substance, then a visible inflammatory reaction will usually occur within 30 minutes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] This response ranges from slight reddening of the skin to a full-blown hive (called "wheal and flare") in more sensitive patients, similar to a mosquito bite.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Interpretation of the results of the skin prick test is usually done by allergists on a severity scale, with +/− meaning borderline reactivity, and 4+ representing a large reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Increasingly, allergists are measuring and recording the diameter of the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Interpretation by well-trained allergists is often guided by relevant literature.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In general, a positive response is interpreted when the wheal of an antigen is ≥3 mm larger than the wheal of the negative control (e.g., saline or glycerin).
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some patients may believe they have determined their own allergic sensitivity from observation.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A skin test is much better than patient observation for allergy detection.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] If a serious life-threatening anaphylactic reaction has brought a patient in for evaluation, some allergists may prefer to perform an initial blood test before conducting a skin prick test.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Skin testing may also not be possible in patients with widespread skin disease or those who have taken antihistamine within the past several days.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Patch testing is a diagnostic method used to identify substances that cause allergic contact dermatitis through a delayed hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] During the procedure, small amounts of potential allergens are applied to the skin, usually on the back, using adhesive patches containing standardized allergen preparations.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The patches are typically left in place for 48 hours, after which the skin is examined for localized eczematous reactions.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Additional readings are commonly performed 72–96 hours after application because allergic contact reactions may develop slowly.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Unlike skin prick testing, which is used to diagnose immediate IgE-mediated allergies, patch testing evaluates delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions mediated by T cells.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergy blood testing, typically measuring allergen-specific IgE, is a quick test that can be ordered by a qualified healthcare professional.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Unlike skin-prick testing, it is not affected by antihistamines and may be used when skin testing is impractical, such as in people with extensive eczema or other skin disease, in pregnancy, or when there is concern about provoking symptoms.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It can be performed in adults and children, including infants, although results must be interpreted together with the clinical history because sensitisation does not always mean clinical allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] An allergy blood test is available through most laboratories.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A sample of the patient's blood is sent to a laboratory for analysis, and the results are sent back a few days later.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Multiple allergens can be detected with a single blood sample.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergy blood tests are very safe because the person is not exposed to any allergens during the testing procedure.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] After the onset of anaphylaxis or a severe allergic reaction, guidelines recommend that emergency departments obtain a time-sensitive blood test to measure tryptase levels and assess for mast cells activation.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The test measures the concentration of specific IgE antibodies in the blood.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Quantitative IgE test results increase the possibility of ranking how different substances may affect symptoms.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A rule of thumb is that the higher the IgE antibody value, the greater the likelihood of symptoms.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergens found at low levels that today do not result in symptoms cannot predict future symptom development.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The quantitative allergy blood result can help determine what a patient is allergic to, predict and monitor disease progression, estimate the risk of a severe reaction, and explain cross-reactivity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A low total IgE level is not adequate to rule out sensitization to commonly inhaled allergens.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Statistical methods, such as ROC curves, predictive value calculations, and likelihood ratios have been used to examine the relationship of various testing methods to each other.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] These methods have shown that patients with high total IgE have a high probability of allergic sensitization, but further investigation with allergy tests for specific IgE antibodies for a carefully chosen set of allergens is often warranted.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Laboratory methods to measure specific IgE antibodies for allergy testing include enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, radioallergosorbent test, fluorescent enzyme immunoassay, and chemiluminescence immunoassay.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Before a diagnosis of allergic disease can be confirmed, other plausible causes of the presenting symptoms must be considered.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Vasomotor rhinitis, for example, is one of many illnesses that share symptoms with allergic rhinitis, underscoring the need for professional differential diagnosis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Once a diagnosis of asthma, rhinitis, anaphylaxis, or other allergic disease has been made, there are several methods for discovering the causative agent of that allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Giving peanut products early in childhood may decrease the risk of allergies, and only breastfeeding during at least the first few months of life may decrease the risk of allergic dermatitis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] There is little evidence that a mother's diet during pregnancy or breastfeeding affects the risk of allergies, although there has been some research to show that irregular cow's milk exposure might increase the risk of cow's milk allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] There is some evidence that delayed introduction of certain foods is useful, and that early exposure to potential allergens may actually be protective.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Following revisions to US and UK pediatric guidelines in 2015 and 2017 that encouraged introducing peanut products to high-risk infants at four to six months of age, one 2025 analysis found a 43% drop in the frequency of peanut allergies, with an estimated 40,000 cases prevented.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] According to that report, some pediatric experts have cautioned that real-world implementation of the guidelines may be inconsistent.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Fish oil supplementation during pregnancy is associated with a lower risk of food sensitivities.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Probiotic supplements during pregnancy or infancy may help to prevent atopic dermatitis.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Management of allergies typically involves avoiding the allergy trigger and taking medications to relieve symptoms.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergen immunotherapy may be useful for some types of allergies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Several medications may be used to block the actions of allergic mediators, prevent cell activation, and degranulation processes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] These include antihistamines, glucocorticoids, epinephrine (adrenaline), mast cell stabilizers, and antileukotriene agents are common treatments of allergic diseases.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Anticholinergics, decongestants, and other compounds thought to impair eosinophil chemotaxis are also commonly used.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Although rare, the severity of anaphylaxis often requires epinephrine injection, and where medical care is unavailable, a device known as an epinephrine autoinjector may be used.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Allergen immunotherapy is useful for environmental allergies, allergies to insect bites, and asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Its benefit for food allergies is unclear and thus not recommended.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Immunotherapy involves exposing people to larger and larger amounts of allergen in an effort to change the immune system's response.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Meta-analyses have found that injections of allergens under the skin is effective in the treatment in allergic rhinitis in children and in asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The benefits may last for years after treatment is stopped.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It is generally safe and effective for allergic rhinitis and conjunctivitis, allergic forms of asthma, and stinging insects.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] To a lesser extent, the evidence also supports the use of sublingual immunotherapy for rhinitis and asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] For seasonal allergies the benefit is small.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In this form the allergen is given under the tongue and people often prefer it to injections.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Immunotherapy is not recommended as a stand-alone treatment for asthma.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] An experimental treatment, enzyme potentiated desensitization (EPD), has been tried for decades but is not generally accepted as effective.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] EPD uses dilutions of allergen and an enzyme, beta-glucuronidase, to which T-regulatory lymphocytes are supposed to respond by favoring desensitization, or down-regulation, rather than sensitization.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] EPD has also been tried for the treatment of autoimmune diseases, but evidence does not show effectiveness.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A review found no effectiveness of homeopathic treatments and no difference compared with placebo.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The authors concluded that, based on rigorous clinical trials of all types of homeopathy for childhood and adolescent ailments, there is no convincing evidence that supports the use of homeopathic treatments.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The allergic diseases—hay fever and asthma—have increased in the Western world over the past 2–3 decades.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Increases in allergic asthma and other atopic disorders in industrialized nations, it is estimated, began in the 1960s and 1970s, with further increases occurring during the 1980s and 1990s, although some suggest that a steady rise in sensitization has been occurring since the 1920s.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The number of new cases per year of atopy in developing countries has, in general, remained much lower.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Although genetic factors govern susceptibility to atopic disease, increases in atopy have occurred within too short a period to be explained by a genetic change in the population, thus pointing to environmental or lifestyle changes.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Several hypotheses have been identified to explain this increased rate.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Increased exposure to perennial allergens may be due to housing changes and increased time spent indoors, and changes in cleanliness may decrease activation of a common immune control mechanisms or hygiene, and exacerbated by dietary changes, obesity, and decline in physical exercise.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The hygiene hypothesis maintains that high living standards and hygienic conditions expose children to fewer infections.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It is thought that reduced bacterial and viral infections early in life direct the maturing immune system away from TH1 type responses, leading to unrestrained TH2 responses that allow for an increase in allergy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Changes in rates and types of infection alone, however, have been unable to explain the observed increase in allergic disease, and recent evidence has focused attention on the importance of the gastrointestinal microbial environment.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] It is speculated that these infections exert their effect by critically altering TH1/TH2 regulation.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Important elements of newer hygiene hypotheses also include exposure to endotoxins, exposure to pets and growing up on a farm.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Some symptoms attributable to allergic diseases are mentioned in ancient sources.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Particularly, three members of the Roman Julio-Claudian dynasty (Augustus, Claudius and Britannicus) are suspected to have a family history of atopy.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The concept of "allergy" was originally introduced in 1906 by the Viennese pediatrician Clemens von Pirquet, after he noticed that patients who had received injections of horse serum or smallpox vaccine usually had quicker, more severe reactions to second injections.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Pirquet called this phenomenon "allergy" from the Ancient Greek words ἄλλος *allos* meaning "other" and ἔργον *ergon* meaning "work".
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] All forms of hypersensitivity were previously classified as allergies, and all were thought to be caused by an improper activation of the immune system.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Later, it became clear that several disease mechanisms were implicated, with a common link to disordered immune system activation.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In 1963, a new classification scheme was designed by Philip Gell and Robin Coombs that described four types of hypersensitivity reactions, known as Type I to Type IV hypersensitivity.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] With this new classification, the word *allergy*, sometimes clarified as a *true allergy*, was restricted to type I hypersensitivities (also called immediate hypersensitivity), which are characterized as rapidly developing reactions involving IgE antibodies.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] A breakthrough in understanding the mechanisms of allergy was the discovery of the antibody class labeled immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] IgE was simultaneously discovered in 1966–67 by two independent groups: Ishizaka's team at the Children's Asthma Research Institute and Hospital in Denver, USA, and by Gunnar Johansson and Hans Bennich in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Their joint paper was published in April 1969.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] Radiometric assays include the radioallergosorbent test (RAST test) method, which uses IgE-binding (anti-IgE) antibodies labeled with radioactive isotopes for quantifying the levels of IgE antibody in the blood.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The RAST methodology was invented and marketed in 1974 by Pharmacia Diagnostics AB, Uppsala, Sweden, and the acronym RAST is actually a brand name.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] In 1989, Pharmacia Diagnostics AB replaced it with a superior test named the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, which uses the newer fluorescence-labeled technology.
[src:avocado/allergic-p01] The updated version, the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, is the only specific IgE assay the Food and Drug Administration has approved to quantitatively report to its detection limit of 0.1 kU/L.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] The medical speciality that studies, diagnoses, and treats diseases caused by allergies is called allergology.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] An allergist is a physician specially trained to manage and treat allergies, asthma, and other allergic diseases.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] Becoming an allergist/immunologist requires completion of at least nine years of training.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] After completing medical school and graduating with a medical degree, a physician will undergo three years of training in internal medicine (to become an internist) or pediatrics (to become a pediatrician).
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] Internists or pediatricians wishing to focus on the sub-specialty of allergy-immunology then complete at least an additional two years of study, called a fellowship, in an allergy/immunology training program.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] Allergists/immunologists listed as ABAI-certified have successfully passed the certifying ABAI examination following their fellowship.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] In the United Kingdom, allergy is a subspecialty of general medicine or pediatrics.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] After obtaining postgraduate exams (MRCP or MRCPCH), a doctor works for several years as a specialist registrar before qualifying for the General Medical Council specialist register.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] Allergy services may also be delivered by immunologists.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] A 2003 Royal College of Physicians report presented a case for improvement of what were felt to be inadequate allergy services in the UK.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] In 2006, the House of Lords convened a subcommittee.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] It concluded likewise in 2007 that allergy services were insufficient to deal with what the Lords referred to as an "allergy epidemic" and its social cost; it made several recommendations.
[src:avocado/allergic-p02] Low-allergen foods are being developed, as are improvements in skin prick test predictions; evaluation of the atopy patch test, wasp sting outcomes predictions, a rapidly disintegrating epinephrine tablet, and anti-IL-5 for eosinophilic diseases.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The **American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals** (**ASPCA**) is a non-profit organization dedicated to preventing animal cruelty.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It is the oldest animal welfare organization in the United States.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] On February 8, 1866, Bergh pleaded on behalf of animals at a meeting at Clinton Hall in New York City.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Some of the issues he discussed were cockfighting and the horrors of slaughterhouses.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] After getting signatures for his "Declaration of the Rights of Animals," Bergh was given an official charter to incorporate the ASPCA on April 10, 1866.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] On April 19, 1866, the first anti-cruelty law was passed in NY since the founding of ASPCA, and the organization was granted the right to enforce anti-cruelty laws.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1867, ASPCA operated its first ambulance for injured horses and began advocating for more humane treatment of animals such as horses, live pigeons, cats, and dogs.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Early goals of ASPCA focused on efforts for horses and livestock, since at the time they were used for a number of activities.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1918, ASPCA veterinarians developed the use of anesthesia and as a result were able to work on a horse with a broken kneecap.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1954, ASPCA hospitals added pathology and radiography laboratories and programs.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1961, ASPCA veterinarians performed their first open-heart surgery on a dog.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] From 1894 to 1994, the ASPCA operated the municipal animal shelter system in New York City which euthanized unadopted animals.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Starting in 1977, the ASPCA entered into a contract with the New York City Department of Health to receive municipal funding to operate the shelter system.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The contract rendered the ASPCA increasingly reliant on government income rather than private donations, and subject to the effects of annual city budget appropriations.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1993, the ASPCA decided not to renew its contract for operating the shelter system.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Operation of the shelter system was transferred to Center for Animal Care and Control, later renamed Animal Care Centers of NYC, in 1995.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1996, ASPCA acquired the Animal Poison Control Center from the University of Illinois.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2013, the ASPCA made a $25 million commitment to assist at-risk animals and pet owners in the greater Los Angeles metropolitan area, including a fully subsidized spay/neuter facility in South Los Angeles operated by the ASPCA and a campaign to encourage the fostering of local vulnerable kittens.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA spoke out in support of New York City's new mayor's (Bill de Blasio) campaign to ban horse-drawn carriages in the city.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA opened the Gloria Gurney Canine Annex for Recovery & Enrichment (CARE) in NYC to house dogs brought by the NYPD to the ASPCA in connection with animal cruelty investigations.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA also opened the ASPCA Kitten Nursery in NYC to care for neonate and very young homeless kittens until they are appropriate for adoption.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2015, ASPCA acquired the Asheville, North Carolina–based Humane Alliance, now called the ASPCA Spay/Neuter Alliance.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2018, ASPCA established the ASPCA Behavioral Rehabilitation Center.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Located in Weaverville, North Carolina, the Center provides behavioral rehabilitation to canine victims of cruelty and neglect.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The center's Learning Lab also disseminates rehabilitative aid and training to shelters around the country.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2019, ASPCA opened the ASPCA Community Veterinary Center in Liberty City, Miami, Florida, to provide subsidized veterinary services for an underserved community.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It also took over responsibility for The Right Horse Initiative as an official program of the ASPCA in 2019.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2020, ASPCA opened the ASPCA Community Veterinary Center in the Bronx, New York.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2021, the Society opened the ASPCA Community Veterinary Center supported by the Alex and Elisabeth Lewyt Charitable Trust, in NYC.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of 2023, ASPCA's New York hospital was treating 9,000–10,000 patients annually.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2023, ASPCA began releasing an annual report that grades major grocery retailers in the United States on their policies around animal welfare, such as selling cage-free eggs and pork raised without gestation crates.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] An ASPCA fundraising commercial featuring Sarah McLachlan began airing in early 2007.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] By December 2008, it had raised more than $30 million for the ASPCA, becoming the organization's most successful fundraising campaign.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The *New York Times* reported that the spot became known as "The Ad" in non-profit circles.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2021, CBS News reported that the ad misled donors, who believed that their financial contributions supported local SPCAs and animal welfare charities.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The CBS News investigation focused on "questions about whether the money is going where donors expect," reporting the ASPCA raised $2 billion for animal welfare between 2008 and 2019 and spent only $146 million in grants to local animal welfare groups.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In response, a spokesperson for the ASPCA said that donors were aware that the ASPCA was not an umbrella organization for local organizations with SPCA in their names.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] After the CBS News piece aired, two widely-shared posts on Facebook claimed that the ASPCA's CEO was paid $600,000 annually, and that only three cents of each dollar donated were used "for veterinary supplies and for transporting the animals".
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] *USA Today* fact-checked the posts and found that based on ASPCA tax filings, 34.4% of the ASPCA's budget was used for shelter and veterinary care, and an average of 75.1% of expenses were used to support its mission statement.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2012, the ASPCA agreed to pay Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus $9.3 million to settle a lawsuit regarding the ASPCA's false allegations of animal cruelty by the circus.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Courts found that ASPCA activists had paid the key witness, a former Ringling barn helper, at least $190,000, making him "essentially a paid plaintiff" who lacked credibility.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Sayres stepped down as CEO in 2012, and in 2013 longtime ASPCA staff member Matthew Bershadker was named president and CEO.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA's Government Relations, Legal Advocacy and Investigations departments work with state and federal lawmakers and engage in legislative and litigation efforts to secure stronger legal protections for animals.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Some of the animal welfare issues the departments work on include ending puppy mills and breed-specific legislation.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Department of Agriculture for access to animal breeder inspection records.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The filed lawsuit claimed that Defendants-Appellees the U.S.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA was among the animal welfare groups that supported the "puppy mill pipeline" bill in New York, which was signed by Governor Kathy Hochul on December 15, 2022.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The law went into effect in 2024 and makes it illegal to sell dogs, cats, and rabbits in pet stores in New York.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization's senior director of state legislation said the law is needed because many puppies are imported from other states where New York does not have jurisdiction to inspect the conditions in the breeding facility.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] At the invitation of local agencies, ASPCA deploys to sites of large-scale animal abuse, animal neglect, natural disasters, or man-made disasters in which animals are at risk.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Teams, including National Field Response, Legal Advocacy and Investigations, Forensic Sciences, the Cruelty Recovery Center, Relocation and the Behavioral Sciences team, engage in animal rescue efforts.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] They provide behavioral and medical treatment for the animals and support the prosecution of criminal cases with forensic science, evidence collection and analysis, and legal and expert testimony support.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Cases involving torture, killings and mistreatment of animals are some examples of cases handled by the ASPCA.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] A common example was displayed in the news in October 2008, when ASPCA was in charge of an investigation involving the slaughtering of a beagle that lived in the Bronx.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2016, ASPCA field deployment teams participated in a large animal cruelty rescue operation, rescuing nearly 700 animals from an unlicensed facility in North Carolina.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In September 2013, after many years of providing humane law enforcement services in NYC, the ASPCA and the New York City Police Department announced a collaboration to provide enhanced protection to New York City's animals.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In this partnership, the NYPD responds to all animal cruelty complaints throughout New York City, while the ASPCA provides medical and behavioral care for animal cruelty victims and provides legal and forensic assistance in the prosecution of cases.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA Community Engagement team also works closely with the NYPD to connect pets in need to services such as medical care, grooming and pet supplies.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2020, ASPCA also opened the ASPCA Veterinary Forensic Science Center in Gainesville, Florida, to assist law enforcement with animal cruelty investigations and prosecutions.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Between 2010 and 2025, ASPCA helped investigate 300 dogfighting cases that resulted in the rescue of 6,000 dogs.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2013, ASPCA cared for 367 dogs that were rescued from Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia and Texas from what was the second largest dogfighting ring in the United States to date.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization sheltered the dogs in an air conditioned, converted warehouse, providing medical and behavioral rehabilitation.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Alabama Media Group reported that none of the dogs had to be euthanized.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization partnered with the National Museum of Crime and Punishment to provide items for an exhibit on dogfighting in 2013.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA worked with the Kansas Bureau of Investigation in 2018 to rescue 45 dogs and nine puppies from a dogfighting ring in Bendena, Kansas.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The investigation also included the organization uncovering dogfighting paraphernalia, like treadmills and chains.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2025, ASPCA partnered with the State of South Carolina to prosecute dogfighting rings and issued 15 related search warrants.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In March of that year, it sheltered and cared for 28 dogs rescued from a single dogfighting ring in Luzerne County.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Following natural disasters, ASPCA provides on the ground assistance providing displaced animals food and shelter.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It also provides grants for other organizations to invest in climate-related disaster preparedness, such as purchasing emergency supplies, power generators, and animal transport units.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA reported assisting at least 550 animals following Hurricane Florence.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] After a Hurricane in Monroe County, Mississippi, the organization partnered with local human societies and Mississippi State University's veterinary program to relocate and give animals medical checks.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2024, after Hurricane Helene its disaster response team provided pet supplies, medication, and veterinary support to affected communities in Florida, Georgia, and North Carolina.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA partnered with a Texas-based animal response team to evacuate over 100 displaced animals after storm-related flooding damaged a shelter at Pilot Point, Texas.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It provided shelter as well as medical and behavioral care for the animals.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Following the 2025 California wildfires, ASPCA announced a $5 million dollar fund for animal welfare organizations in Los Angeles county.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA's Right Horse Initiative is focused on increasing the number of successful horse adoptions in the U.S. and improving the number of positive outcomes for horses in transition as they move from one home, career, or owner to the next.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA works with other animal welfare organizations and rescue groups to relocate animals from areas with high rates of euthanasia in animal shelters to locations with higher adoption rates.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Often, animals are moved from the southern to northern U.S. states.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Animals may be transported using aircraft or vehicles, sometimes being relayed between transporters multiple times along the way.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of March 2022, ASPCA had a fleet of 18 vans used for transport.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization relocated approximately 200,000 animals between 2017 and 2022.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA operates centers where dogs that have experienced abuse or trauma receive treatment and behavior rehabilitation before being cleared for adoption.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of 2022, the organization has committed $40 million to building and operating the centers, which are located in Weaverville, North Carolina, Columbus, Ohio, with another being developed in Pawling, New York.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The Weaverville center opened in 2020 and was the world's first clinic for treating dogs that have been severely traumatized.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The concept was conceived in 2010 by two ASPCA behaviorists as a way to reduce the number of dogs that are euthanized in shelters for behavior issues.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization piloted the program in 2013 at a temporary site in Madison, New Jersey and reported that approximately 90 percent of the dogs treated recovered enough to be adopted.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA purchased land in Weaverville where it built the center.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of July 2022, the Weaverville center had 35 full-time staff, and had rehabilitated 500 dogs since opening.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA published *The Animal Kingdom* magazine in the 1870s which became *Our Animal Friends: An Illustrated Monthly Magazine* in the 1890s.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The magazine featured articles from well known authors of the day, including Louisa May Alcott and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It was renamed *Animal Protection* (1947–1977) and later became *ASPCA Bulletin* (1977–1981), *ASPCA Quarterly Report* (1981–1989), *ASPCA Report* (1989–1992) and *Animal Watch: The Magazine of the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals* (1993–2004).
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1964, Lloyd Alexander authored their history, *Fifty Years in the Doghouse* which was commissioned by the ASPCA.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Copies of the ASPCA's magazine *Animal Protection* are digitized and stored at NC State University Libraries.
[src:avocado/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA currently publishes the *ASPCA Action* magazine.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The **Americas**, sometimes collectively called **America**, are a landmass comprising the totality of North America and South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] When viewed as a single continent, the Americas are the second largest continent by area after Asia and the third largest continent by population.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere and constitute the "New World", in contrast to the "Old World" of Afro-Eurasia.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Along with their associated islands, the Americas cover 8% of Earth's total surface area and 28.4% of its land area.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The topography is dominated by the American Cordillera, a long chain of mountains that runs the length of the west coast.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The flatter eastern side of the Americas is dominated by large river basins, such as the Amazon, St.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Lawrence River–Great Lakes, Mississippi, and La Plata basins.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Since the Americas extend 14,000 km (8,700 mi) from north to south, the climate and ecology vary widely, from the arctic tundra of Northern Canada, Greenland, and Alaska, to the tropical rainforests in Central America and South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Humans first settled the Americas from Asia between 20,000 and 16,000 years ago.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] A second migration of Na-Dene speakers followed later from Asia.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The subsequent migration of the Inuit into the neoarctic c.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] 3500 BCE completed what is generally regarded as the settlement by the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Norse colonization of North America saw several settlements established in Greenland, and perhaps on the mainland, however, these were later abandoned.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Spanish presence involved the enslavement of large numbers of the indigenous population of the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Diseases introduced from Europe and West Africa devastated the indigenous peoples, and the European powers colonized the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Mass emigration from Europe, including large numbers of indentured servants, and importation of African slaves largely replaced the indigenous peoples in much of the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution in the 1770s and largely ended with the Spanish–American War in the late 1890s.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Americas are home to more than a billion inhabitants, two-thirds of whom reside in the United States, Brazil, and Mexico.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The name "America" was first recorded in 1507.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] A world map created by Martin Waldseemüller was the earliest recorded use of the term.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The name was also used (together with the related term *Amerigen*) in the *Cosmographiae Introductio*, apparently written by Matthias Ringmann, in reference to South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] It was applied to both North and South America by Gerardus Mercator in 1538.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] "America" derives from *Americus*, the Latin version of the Italian explorer Amerigo Vespucci's first name.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The feminine form *America* was originally used to refer to the newly discovered continent, which is why it was accorded with the feminine names of the other continents: Asia, Africa, and Europa.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Since the 1950s, however, North America and South America have generally been considered by English speakers as separate continents, and taken together are called *the Americas*, or more rarely *America*.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] When conceived as a unitary continent, the form is generally *the continent of America* in the singular.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] However, without a clarifying context, singular *America* in English commonly refers to the United States of America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The region was initially termed America or New India on the Mercator maps.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Speakers of English generally refer to the landmasses of North America and South America as *the Americas*, the *Western Hemisphere*, or the *New World*.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The adjective *American* may be used to indicate something pertaining to the Americas, but this term is primarily used in English to indicate something pertaining to the United States.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Some non-ambiguous alternatives exist, such as the adjective *Pan-American*, or *New Worlder* as a demonym for a resident of the closely related New World.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Use of *America* in the hemispherical sense is sometimes retained, or can occur when translated from other languages.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] For example, the Association of National Olympic Committees (ANOC) in Paris maintains a single continental association for "America", represented by one of the five Olympic rings.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Mencken said, "The Latin-Americans use Norteamericano in formal writing, but, save in Panama, prefer nicknames in colloquial speech." To avoid "American" one can use constructed terms in their languages derived from "United States" or even "North America".
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In Canada, its southern neighbor is often referred to as "the United States", "the U.S.A.", or (informally) "the States", while U.S. citizens are generally referred to as "Americans".
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Most Canadians resent being referred to as "Americans".
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In Spanish, *América* is a single continent composed of the subcontinents of *América del Sur* and *América del Norte*, the land bridge of *América Central*, and the islands of the *Antillas*.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] *Americano* or *americana* in Spanish refers to a person from *América* in a similar way that in which *europeo* or *europea* refers to a person from *Europa*.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The terms *sudamericano/a*, *centroamericano/a*, *antillano/a* and *norteamericano/a* can be used to more specifically refer to the location where a person may live.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Also, the term *norteamericano* (North American) may refer to a citizen of the United States, though in formal writing it is less common since it is used for the inhabitants of North America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In Portuguese, *América* is a single continent composed of *América do Sul* (South America), *América Central* (Central America) and *América do Norte* (North America).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] It can be ambiguous, as *América* can be used to refer to the United States of America, but is avoided in print and formal environments.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The demonym 'American' (americano) is commonly used in Portuguese to refer to people from the United States, although the terms 'norte-americano', 'estadounidense' or 'estadunidense' also formally exist and are preferred by those who wish to distinguish it from the continental demonym.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In French, the word *américain* may be used for things relating to the Americas; however, similar to English, it is most often used for things relating to the United States, with the term *états-unien* sometimes used for clarity.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] *Panaméricain* may be used as an adjective to refer to the Americas without ambiguity.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] French speakers may use the noun *Amérique* to refer to the whole landmass as one continent, or two continents, *Amérique du Nord* and *Amérique du Sud*.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In French, *Amérique* is seldom used to refer to the United States, leading to some ambiguity when it is.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Similar to English usage, *les Amériques* or *des Amériques* is used to refer unambiguously to the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In Dutch, the word *Amerika* mostly refers to the United States.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Although the United States is equally often referred to as *de Verenigde Staten* ("the United States") or *de VS* ("the US"), *Amerika* relatively rarely refers to the Americas, but it is the only commonly used Dutch word for the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] This often leads to ambiguity; and to stress that something concerns the Americas as a whole, Dutch uses a combination, namely *Noord- en Zuid-Amerika* (North and South America).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Latin America and Central America are generally referred to as *Latijns Amerika* and *Midden-Amerika* respectively.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The adjective *Amerikaans* is most often used for things or people relating to the United States.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] There are no alternative words to distinguish between things relating to the United States or to the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Dutch uses the local alternative for things relating to elsewhere in the Americas, such as *Argentijns* for Argentine, etc.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The term *Pre-Columbian* is used especially often in the context of the great indigenous civilizations of the Americas, such as those of Mesoamerica (Olmec, Toltec, Teotihuacano, Zapotec, Mixtec, Aztec, Maya) and the Andean civilizations (Inca, Moche, Chavín, Muisca, Cañari).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Many pre-Columbian civilizations established characteristics and hallmarks which included permanent or urban settlements, agriculture, civic and monumental architecture, and complex societal hierarchies.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Some of these civilizations had long faded by the time of the first permanent European arrivals (c. late 15th–early 16th centuries), and are known only through archeological investigations.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Others were contemporary with this period, and are also known from historical accounts of the time.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] A few, such as the Maya, had their own written records.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] However, most Europeans of the time viewed such texts as pagan, and much was destroyed in Christian pyres.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Only a few hidden documents remain today, leaving modern historians with glimpses of ancient culture and knowledge.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The first inhabitants migrated into the Americas from Asia.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Habitation sites are known in Alaska and Yukon from at least 20,000 years ago, with suggested ages of up to 40,000 years.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Beyond that, the specifics of the Paleo-Indian migration to and throughout the Americas, including the dates and routes traveled, are subject to ongoing research and discussion.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Widespread habitation of the Americas occurred after the Late Glacial Maximum, from 16,000 to 13,000 years ago.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The traditional theory has been that these early migrants moved into the Beringia land bridge between eastern Siberia and present-day Alaska about 40,000–17,000 years ago, when sea levels were significantly lowered during the Quaternary glaciation.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] These people are believed to have followed herds of now-extinct pleistocene megafauna along *ice-free corridors* that stretched between the Laurentide and Cordilleran ice sheets.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Another route proposed is that, either on foot or using primitive boats, they migrated down the Pacific coast to South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Evidence of the latter would since have been covered by a sea level rise of hundreds of meters following the last ice age.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Both routes may have been taken, although the genetic evidences suggests a single founding population.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The micro-satellite diversity and distributions specific to South American Indigenous peoples indicates that certain populations have been isolated since the initial colonization of the region.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] A second migration occurred after the initial peopling of the Americas; Na Dene speakers, found predominantly in North American groups at varying genetic rates, with the highest frequency found among the Athabaskans at 42%, derive from this second wave.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Linguists and biologists have reached a similar conclusion based on analysis of Amerindian language groups and ABO blood group system distributions.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Then the people of the Arctic small tool tradition, a broad cultural entity that developed along the Alaska Peninsula, around Bristol Bay, and on the eastern shores of the Bering Strait c.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Arctic small tool tradition, a Paleo-Eskimo culture, branched off into two cultural variants, including the Pre-Dorset and the Independence traditions of Greenland.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The descendants of the Pre-Dorset cultural group, the Dorset culture, were displaced by the final migrants from the Bering sea coast line, the Thule people (the ancestors of modern Inuit), by 1000 CE.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Around the same time as the Inuit migrated into Greenland, Viking settlers began arriving in Greenland in 982 and Vinland shortly thereafter, establishing a settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows, near the northernmost tip of Newfoundland.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Although there had been previous trans-oceanic contact, large-scale European colonization of the Americas began with the first voyage of Christopher Columbus in 1492.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The first Spanish settlement in the Americas was La Isabela in northern Hispaniola.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] This town was abandoned shortly after in favor of Santo Domingo de Guzmán, founded in 1496, the oldest American city of European foundation.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] This was the base from which the Spanish monarchy administered its new colonies and their expansion.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Santo Domingo was subject to frequent raids by English and French pirates.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] On the continent, Panama City on the Pacific coast of Central America, founded on August 15, 1519, played an important role, being the base for the Spanish conquest of South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Conquistador Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón established San Miguel de Guadalupe, the first European settlement in what is now the United States, on the Pee Dee River in South Carolina.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] During the first half of the 16th century, Spanish colonists conducted raids throughout the Caribbean Basin, bringing captives from Central America, northern South America, and Florida back to Hispaniola and other Spanish settlements.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] France, led by Jacques Cartier and Giovanni da Verrazzano, focused primarily on North America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] English explorations of the Americas were led by Giovanni Caboto and Sir Walter Raleigh.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Dutch in New Netherland confined their operations to Manhattan Island, Long Island, the Hudson River Valley, and what later became New Jersey.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The spread of new diseases brought by Europeans and African slaves killed many of the inhabitants of North America and South America, with a general population crash of Native Americans occurring in the mid-16th century, often well ahead of European contact.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] One of the most devastating diseases was smallpox.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] European immigrants were often part of state-sponsored attempts to found colonies in the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Migration continued as people moved to the Americas fleeing religious persecution or seeking economic opportunities.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Millions of individuals were forcibly transported to the Americas as slaves, prisoners or indentured servants.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Decolonization of the Americas began with the American Revolution and the Haitian Revolution in the late 1700s.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] This was followed by numerous Latin American wars of independence in the early 1800s.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Between 1811 and 1825, Paraguay, Argentina, Chile, Gran Colombia, the United Provinces of Central America, Mexico, Brazil, Peru, and Bolivia gained independence from Spain and Portugal in armed revolutions.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] After the Dominican Republic won independence from Haiti, it was re-annexed by Spain in 1861, but reclaimed its independence in 1865 at the conclusion of the Dominican Restoration War.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The last violent episode of decolonization was the Cuban War of Independence which became the Spanish–American War, which resulted in the independence of Cuba in 1898, and the transfer of sovereignty over Puerto Rico from Spain to the United States.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Peaceful decolonization began with the United States's purchase of Louisiana from France in 1803, Florida from Spain in 1819, Alaska from Russia in 1867, and the Danish West Indies from Denmark in 1916.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Canada became independent of the United Kingdom, starting with the Balfour Declaration of 1926 and the Statute of Westminster 1931 and ending with the patriation of the Canadian Constitution in 1982.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Dominion of Newfoundland similarly achieved independence under the Balfour Declaration and Statute of Westminster, but relinquished self-rule in 1934.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] It was subsequently confederated with Canada in 1949.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The remaining European colonies in the Caribbean began to achieve peaceful independence well after World War II.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago became independent in 1962, and Guyana and Barbados both achieved independence in 1966.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the 1970s, the Bahamas, Grenada, Dominica, St.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Vincent and the Grenadines all became independent of the United Kingdom, and Suriname became independent of the Netherlands.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Belize, Antigua and Barbuda, and Saint Kitts and Nevis achieved independence from the United Kingdom in the 1980s.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Americas make up most of the land in Earth's Western Hemisphere.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The northernmost point of the Americas is Kaffeklubben Island, which is the most northerly point of land on Earth.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The southernmost undisputed point is Águila Islet, although the Antarctic islands of Southern Thule are sometimes taken into account.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The mainland of the Americas is the world's longest north-to-south landmass.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The distance between its two polar extremities, Murchison Promontory on the Boothia Peninsula in northern Canada and Cape Froward in Chilean Patagonia, is roughly 14,000 km (8,700 mi).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The mainland's most westerly point is the end of the Seward Peninsula in Alaska; Attu Island, further off the Alaskan coast to the west, is considered the westernmost point of the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Ponta do Seixas in northeastern Brazil forms the easternmost extremity of the mainland, while Nordostrundingen, in Greenland, is the most easterly point of the continental shelf.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] South America broke off from the west of the supercontinent Gondwana about 135 million years ago, forming its own continent.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] About 15 million years ago, the collision of the Caribbean Plate and the Pacific Plate resulted in the emergence of a series of volcanoes along the border that created a number of islands.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The gaps in the archipelago of Central America filled in with material eroded off North America and South America, plus new land created by continued volcanism.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] By three million years ago, the continents of North America and South America were linked by the Isthmus of Panama, thereby forming the single landmass of the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Great American Interchange resulted in many species being spread across the Americas, such as the cougar, procyonids, porcupines, opossums, armadillos, and hummingbirds.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The geography of the western Americas is dominated by the American Cordillera, with the Andes running along the west coast of South America and the Rocky Mountains and other North American Cordillera ranges running along the western side of North America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The 2,300-kilometer-long (1,400 mi) Appalachian Mountains run along the east coast of North America from Alabama to Newfoundland.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] North of the Appalachians, the Arctic Cordillera runs along the eastern coast of Canada.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The largest mountain ranges are the Andes and Rocky Mountains.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Sierra Nevada and the Cascade Range reach similar altitudes as the Rocky Mountains, but are significantly smaller.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In North America, the greatest number of fourteeners are in the United States, and more specifically in the US state of Colorado.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The highest peaks of the Americas are located in the Andes, with Aconcagua of Argentina being the highest; in North America Denali (Mount McKinley) in the US state of Alaska is the tallest.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Between its coastal mountain ranges, North America has vast flat areas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Interior Plains spread over much of the continent, with low relief.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Canadian Shield covers almost 5 million km2 of North America and is generally quite flat.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Similarly, the north-east of South America is covered by the flat Amazon basin.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Brazilian Highlands on the east coast are fairly smooth but show some variations in landform, while farther south the Gran Chaco and Pampas are broad lowlands.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The climate of the Americas varies significantly from region to region.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Tropical rainforest climate occurs in the latitudes of the Amazon, American cloud forests, southeastern Florida and Darién Gap.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the Rocky Mountains and Andes, dry and continental climates are observed.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Often the higher altitudes of these mountains are snow-capped.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Southeastern North America is well known for its occurrence of tornadoes and hurricanes, of which the vast majority of tornadoes occur in the United States' Tornado Alley, as well as in the southerly Dixie Alley in the North American late-winter and early spring seasons.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Often parts of the Caribbean are exposed to the violent effects of hurricanes.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] These weather systems are formed by the collision of dry, cool air from Canada and wet, warm air from the Atlantic.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] With coastal mountains and interior plains, the Americas have several large river basins that drain the continents.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The largest river basin in North America is that of the Mississippi, covering the second-largest watershed on the planet.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Mississippi–Missouri river system drains most of 31 states of the United States, most of the Great Plains, and large areas between the Rocky and Appalachian mountains.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Mississippi–Missouri is the fourth-longest river system and has the tenth-greatest discharge in the world.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In North America, to the east of the Appalachian Mountains, there are no major rivers but rather a series of rivers and streams that flow east with their terminus in the Atlantic Ocean, such as the Hudson, Saint John, and Savannah rivers.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] A similar instance arises with central Canadian rivers that drain into Hudson Bay; the largest being the Churchill River.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] On the west coast of North America, the main rivers are the Colorado, Columbia, Yukon, Fraser, and Sacramento rivers.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Colorado River drains much of the Southern Rockies and parts of the Basin and Range Province.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The river flows approximately 1,450 miles (2,330 km) into the Gulf of California, during which over time it has carved out natural phenomena such as the Grand Canyon and created phenomena such as the Salton Sea.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Columbia is a large river, 1,243 miles (2,000 km) long, in central western North America and is the most powerful river on the West Coast of the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the far northwest of North America, the Yukon drains much of the Alaskan peninsula and flows 1,980 miles (3,190 km) from parts of Yukon and the Northwest Territory to the Pacific.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Draining to the Arctic Ocean of Canada, the Mackenzie River drains waters from the Arctic Great Lakes of Arctic Canada, as opposed to the St Lawrence River that drains the Great Lakes of southern Canada into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The Mackenzie River is the largest in Canada and drains 1,805,200 km2 (697,000 mi2).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The largest river basin in South America is that of the Amazon, which has the highest volume flow of any river on Earth.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The second largest watershed of South America is that of the Paraná River, which covers about 2,582,074 km2 (996,944 mi2).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] North America and South America began to develop a shared population of flora and fauna about 2.5 million years ago, when continental drift brought the two continents into contact via the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Initially, the exchange of biota was roughly equal, with North American genera migrating into South America in about the same proportions as South American genera migrated into North America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] This exchange is known as the Great American Interchange.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The exchange became lopsided after roughly a million years, with the total spread of South American genera into North America far more limited in scope than the spread of North American genera into South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In exports and imports, in 2020, the United States was the world's second largest exporter (US$1.64 trillion) and the largest importer (US$2.56 trillion).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Mexico was the tenth largest exporter and importer.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Canada was the twelfth largest exporter and importer.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Brazil was the 24th largest exporter and the 28th largest importer.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Chile was the 45th largest exporter and the 47th largest importer.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Argentina was the 46th largest exporter and the 52nd largest importer.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Colombia was the 54th largest exporter and the 51st largest importer; among others.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] The agriculture of the continent is very strong and varied.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Countries such as United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, and Argentina are among the largest agricultural producers on the planet.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In livestock, the Americas are major producers.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In industrial terms, the World Bank lists the top producing countries each year, based on the total value of production.
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the production of oil, the continent had 8 of the 30 largest world producers in 2020: United States (1st), Canada (4th), Brazil (8th), Mexico (14th), Colombia (20th), Venezuela (26th), Ecuador (27th), and Argentina (28th).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the production of natural gas, the continent had 8 of the 32 largest world producers in 2015: United States (1st), Canada (5th), Argentina (18th), Trinidad and Tobago (20th), Mexico (21st), Venezuela (28th), Bolivia (31st), and Brazil (32nd).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the production of coal, the continent had 5 of the 30 largest world producers in 2018: United States (3rd), Colombia (12th), Canada (13th), Mexico (24th), and Brazil (27th).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the production of vehicles, the continent had 5 of the 30 largest world producers in 2019: United States (2nd), Mexico (7th), Brazil (9th), Canada (12th), and Argentina (28th).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] In the production of steel, the continent had 5 of the 31 largest world producers in 2019: United States (4th), Brazil (9th), Mexico (15th), Canada (18th), and Argentina (31st).
[src:avocado/americas-p01] Haiti has the lowest GDP per capita in the Americas, although its economy was growing slightly as of 2016.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] A city proper is the locality with legally fixed boundaries and an administratively recognized urban status that is usually characterized by some form of local government.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] An urban area is characterized by higher population density and vast human features in comparison to areas surrounding it.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Urban areas may be cities, towns or conurbations, but the term is not commonly extended to rural settlements such as villages and hamlets.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Urban areas are created and further developed by the process of urbanization and do not include large swaths of rural land, as do metropolitan areas.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] that is socio-economically connected to the urban core city, typically by employment ties through commuting, with the urban core city being the primary labor market.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] In accordance with these definitions, the three largest population centers in the Americas are: Mexico City, anchor to the largest metropolitan area in the Americas; New York City, anchor to the largest urban area in the Americas; and São Paulo, the largest city proper in the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] All three cities maintain Alpha classification and large scale influence.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The population of the Americas is made up of the descendants of four large ethnic groups and their combinations.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Latin America is typically contrasted with Anglo-America, where English, a Germanic language, is prevalent, and which comprises Canada (with the exception of Francophone Canada rooted in Latin Europe [France]—see Quebec and Acadia) and the United States.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Both countries are located in North America, with cultures deriving predominantly from British and other Germanic roots.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The transatlantic slave trade brought millions of Africans to the territories of the Americas under the colonial rule of European powers, especially South America.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] In South America, Portugal played a significant role in the trafficking of enslaved Africans, with estimates suggesting that about 40% of all Africans forcibly brought to the Americas were taken to Brazil alone, to work primarily in sugar cane plantations, mining, and agricultural endeavors.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] In North America, the British Empire was heavily involved in the transatlantic slave trade, with the establishment of colonies such as Virginia, where enslaved Africans were primarily used as labor in tobacco plantations and later in other agricultural and domestic sectors.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] This system perpetuated for centuries, shaping the socio-economic landscape of all nations of the hemisphere.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] After the Haitian Revolution led by Jean-Jacques Dessalines, which started in 1791 and was the only successful slave revolt in history, the world's first black republic was established.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] It started with the massacre of the white population, between 3,000 and 5,000 white men and women of all ages were killed.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Oui, nous avons rendu à ces vrais cannibales guerre pour guerre, crimes pour crimes, outrages pour outrages.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Oui, j’ai sauvé mon pays, j’ai vengé l’Amérique.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Yes, I have saved my country – I have avenged America.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Other faiths include Buddhism; Hinduism; Sikhism; Baháʼí Faith; a wide variety of indigenous religions, many of which can be categorized as animistic; new age religions and many African and African-derived religions.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Syncretic faiths can also be found throughout the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Various languages are spoken in the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Some are of European origin, others are spoken by indigenous peoples or are the mixture of various languages like the different creoles.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The most widely spoken first language in the Americas is Spanish, followed by English and Portuguese.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The dominant language of Latin America is Spanish, though the most populous nation in Latin America, Brazil, speaks Portuguese.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Small enclaves of French-, Dutch- and English-speaking regions also exist in Latin America, notably in French Guiana, Suriname, and Belize and Guyana respectively.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Haitian Creole is dominant in the nation of Haiti, where French is also spoken.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Native languages are more prominent in Latin America than in Anglo-America, with Nahuatl, Quechua, Aymara, and Guaraní as the most common.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Various other native languages are spoken with less frequency across both Anglo-America and Latin America.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Creole languages other than Haitian Creole are also spoken in parts of Latin America.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The dominant language of Anglo-America is English.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] French is also official in Canada, where it is the predominant language in Quebec and an official language in New Brunswick along with English.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] It is also an important language in Louisiana, and in parts of New Hampshire, Maine, and Vermont.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Spanish has kept an ongoing presence in the Southwestern United States, which formed part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain, especially in California and New Mexico, where a distinct variety of Spanish spoken since the 17th century has survived.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] It has more recently become widely spoken in other parts of the United States because of heavy immigration from Latin America.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] High levels of immigration in general have brought great linguistic diversity to Anglo-America, with over 300 languages known to be spoken in the United States alone, but most languages are spoken only in small enclaves and by relatively small immigrant groups.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Most of the non-native languages have, to different degrees, evolved differently from the mother country, but are usually still mutually intelligible.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Some have combined, however, which has even resulted in completely new languages, such as Papiamento, which is a combination of Portuguese, Spanish, Dutch (representing the respective colonizers), native Arawak, various African languages, and, more recently English.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The lingua franca Portuñol, a mixture of Portuguese and Spanish, is spoken in the border regions of Brazil and neighboring Spanish-speaking countries.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] More specifically, Riverense Portuñol is spoken by about 100,000 people in the border regions of Brazil and Uruguay.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Because of immigration, there are many communities where other languages are spoken from all parts of the world, especially in the United States, Brazil, Argentina, Canada, Chile, Costa Rica, and Uruguay—very important destinations for immigrants.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in the Americas, having spread through the hemisphere after the growth of US influence in the late 19th century.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] It overtook cricket, a fellow bat-and-ball sport spread by earlier British influence, in most places outside of the Commonwealth Caribbean.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Other American sports, such as basketball, have grown throughout the region over time.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] Football is perhaps the most popular and followed sport in the Americas.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The North American region which also includes the Central and Caribbean national associations is overseen by the CONCACAF, while the South American region and its national teams are represented by the CONMEBOL.
[src:avocado/americas-p02] The following is a list of multinational organizations in the Americas.
[src:avocado/anise] The flavor and aroma of its seeds have similarities with some other spices and herbs, such as star anise, fennel, liquorice, and tarragon.
[src:avocado/anise] It is widely cultivated and used to flavor food, candy, and alcoholic drinks, especially around the Mediterranean.
[src:avocado/anise] The name "anise" is derived via Old French from the Latin words *anīsum* or *anēthum* from Greek ἄνηθον *ánēthon* referring to dill.
[src:avocado/anise] An obsolete English word for anise is *anet*, also coming from *ănēthum*.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise is an herbaceous annual plant growing to 60–90 centimetres (2–3 feet) or more.
[src:avocado/anise] The leaves at the base of the plant are simple, 1–5 cm (3⁄8–2 inches) long and shallowly lobed, while leaves higher on the stems are feathery or lacy, pinnate, divided into numerous small leaflets.
[src:avocado/anise] Both leaves and flowers are produced in large, loose clusters.
[src:avocado/anise] The flowers are either white or yellow, approximately 3 millimetres (1⁄8 in) in diameter, produced in dense umbels.
[src:avocado/anise] The fruit is a dry oblong and curved schizocarp, 4–6 mm (1⁄6–1⁄4 in) long, usually called "aniseed".
[src:avocado/anise] Anise is a food plant for the larvae of some Lepidoptera species (butterflies and moths), including the lime-speck pug and wormwood pug.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise was first cultivated in the Middle East, and was brought to Europe for its medicinal value.
[src:avocado/anise] It has been cultivated in Egypt for approximately 4,000 years.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise plants grow best in light, fertile, well-drained soil.
[src:avocado/anise] The seeds should be planted as soon as the ground warms up in spring.
[src:avocado/anise] Because the plants have a taproot, they do not transplant well after being established so they should either be started in their final location or be transplanted while the seedlings are still small.
[src:avocado/anise] Western cuisines have long used anise to flavor dishes, drinks, and candies.
[src:avocado/anise] The word is used for both the species of herb and its licorice-like flavor.
[src:avocado/anise] The most powerful flavor component of the essential oil of anise, anethole, is found in both anise and an unrelated spice indigenous to South China called star anise (*Illicium verum*) widely used in South Asian, Southeast Asian and East Asian dishes.
[src:avocado/anise] Star anise is considerably less expensive to produce and has gradually displaced *P. anisum* in Western markets.
[src:avocado/anise] While formerly produced in larger quantities, by 1999 world production of the essential oil of anise was 8 tons, compared to 400 tons of star anise.
[src:avocado/anise] As with all spices, the composition of anise varies considerably with origin and cultivation method.
[src:avocado/anise] These are typical values for the main constituents.
[src:avocado/anise] In particular, the anise seeds products should also contain more than 0.2 milliliter volatile oil per 100 grams of spice.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise is sweet and aromatic, distinguished by its characteristic flavor.
[src:avocado/anise] The culinary uses of anise are not limited only to sweets and confections, as it is a key ingredient in Mexican *atole de anís* and *champurrado*, which is similar to hot chocolate.
[src:avocado/anise] In India and Pakistan, it is taken as a digestive after meals, used in brines in the Italian region of Apulia and as a flavoring agent in Italian sausage, pepperoni and other Italian processed meat products.
[src:avocado/anise] The freshly chopped leaves are added to cheese spreads, dips or salads, while roots and stems impart a mild licorice flavor to soups and stews.
[src:avocado/anise] Outside the Mediterranean region, it is found in Colombian *aguardiente* and Mexican *Xtabentún*.
[src:avocado/anise] These liqueurs are clear, but on addition of water become cloudy, a phenomenon known as the ouzo effect or louche.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise is used together with other herbs and spices in some root beers, such as Virgil's in the United States.
[src:avocado/anise] According to Pliny the Elder, anise was used as a cure for sleeplessness, chewed with alexanders and a little honey in the morning to freshen the breath, and, when mixed with wine, as a remedy for asp bites (N.H.
[src:avocado/anise] In 19th-century medicine, anise was prepared as **aqua anisi** ("Water of Anise") in doses of an ounce or more and as **spiritus anisi** ("Spirit of Anise") in doses of 5–20 minims.
[src:avocado/anise] In Turkish folk medicine, its seeds have been used as an appetite stimulant, tranquilizer or diuretic.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise essential oil can be obtained from the fruits by either steam distillation or extraction using supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:avocado/anise] The yield of essential oil is influenced by the growing conditions and extraction process, with supercritical extraction being more efficient.
[src:avocado/anise] Regardless of the method of isolation the main component of the oil is anethole (80–90%), with minor components including 4-anisaldehyde, estragole and pseudoisoeugenyl-2-methylbutyrates amongst others.
[src:avocado/anise] 2008 to be 2–6% extracted oil by weight of raw seed material, 74–94% being *trans*-anethole and the remaining fraction estragole (methylchavicol), anisaldehyde and γ-himachalene.) Anethole is responsible for anise's characteristic odor and flavor.
[src:avocado/anise] Builders of steam locomotives in Britain incorporated capsules of aniseed oil into white metal plain bearings so the distinctive smell would give warning in case of overheating.
[src:avocado/anise] Anise can be made into a liquid scent and is used for both drag hunting and fishing.
[src:avocado/anise] It is put on fishing lures to attract fish.
[src:avocado/avocado] The **avocado**, **alligator pear** or **avocado pear** (***Persea americana***) is an evergreen tree in the laurel family (Lauraceae).
[src:avocado/avocado] It is native to the Americas, with archaeological evidence of early human avocado use dating back thousands of years across various regions of Central and South America.
[src:avocado/avocado] It was prized for its large and unusually oily fruit.
[src:avocado/avocado] The native range of avocado (*Persea americana*) extends from Mexico to Peru, encompassing much of Central America and parts of northern and western South America.
[src:avocado/avocado] Its fruit, sometimes also referred to as an **alligator pear** or **avocado pear**, is botanically a large berry containing a single large seed.
[src:avocado/avocado] Sequencing of its genome showed that the evolution of avocados was shaped by polyploidy events and that commercial varieties have a hybrid origin.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado trees are partly self-pollinating, and are often propagated through grafting to maintain consistent fruit output.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados are presently cultivated in the tropical and Mediterranean climates of many countries.
[src:avocado/avocado] As of 2023, Mexico is the world's leading producer of avocados, supplying 29% of the global harvest of 10.5 million tonnes.
[src:avocado/avocado] The fruit of domestic varieties have smooth, buttery, golden-green flesh when ripe.
[src:avocado/avocado] Depending on the cultivar, avocados have green, brown, purplish, or black skin, and may be pear-shaped, egg-shaped, or spherical.
[src:avocado/avocado] For commercial purposes, the fruits are picked while unripe and ripened after harvesting.
[src:avocado/avocado] The nutrient density and high fat content of avocado flesh are advantages for various cuisines, including vegetarian diets.
[src:avocado/avocado] In major production regions like Chile, Mexico and California, the water demands of avocado farms place strain on local resources.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado production is implicated in other externalities, including deforestation and human rights concerns associated with the partial control of their production in Mexico by organized crime.
[src:avocado/avocado] Global warming is expected to result in significant changes to the suitable growing zones for avocados, and place additional pressures on the locales in which they are produced due to heat waves and drought.
[src:avocado/avocado] Panicles of flowers with deciduous bracts arise from new growth or the axils of leaves.
[src:avocado/avocado] The tree flowers thousands of blossoms every year.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado blossoms sprout from racemes near the leaf axils; they are small and inconspicuous 5–10 mm (3⁄16–3⁄8 in) wide.
[src:avocado/avocado] They have no petals but instead two whorls of three pale-green or greenish-yellow downy perianth lobes, each blossom has 9 stamens with 2 basal orange nectar glands.
[src:avocado/avocado] The avocado fruit is a climacteric, single-seeded berry, due to the imperceptible endocarp covering the seed, rather than a drupe.
[src:avocado/avocado] Early wild avocados prior to domestication had much smaller seeds around 2.1–2.2 centimetres (0.83–0.87 in) in diameter, likely corresponding to smaller fruit size.
[src:avocado/avocado] The species produces various cultivars with larger, fleshier fruits with a thinner exocarp because of selective breeding by humans.
[src:avocado/avocado] The species was scientifically named by the British botanist Philip Miller in 1768.
[src:avocado/avocado] The genus *Persea* to which the avocado belongs is considered to have a North American origin, with *Persea* suggested to have diversified in Central America during the Pleistocene epoch.
[src:avocado/avocado] The modern avocado is thought to have speciated from other *Persea* during the Pleistocene, estimated at around either 1.3 million or 430,000 years ago.
[src:avocado/avocado] A number of authors, including Connie Barlow in her 2001 book *The Ghosts of Evolution*, have speculated that the avocado is an "evolutionary anachronism" with megafaunal dispersal syndrome (a concept originally proposed in the 1980s by Paul S.
[src:avocado/avocado] Janzen), arguing that the avocado likely coevolved dispersal of its large seed by now-extinct megafauna.
[src:avocado/avocado] Barlow proposed that the dispersers included the gomphothere (elephant relative) *Cuvieronius*, as well as ground sloths, toxodontids, and glyptodonts.
[src:avocado/avocado] The concept of evolutionary anachronisms/megafaunal dispersal syndrome has been criticised by some authors, who note that many large fruit are readily dispersed by non-megafaunal animals, with agoutis and spectacled bears having been observed eating domestic avocados.
[src:avocado/avocado] The earliest known written account of the avocado in Europe is that of Martín Fernández de Enciso (c.
[src:avocado/avocado] 1470 – 1528) in 1519 in his book, *Suma De Geographia Que Trata De Todas Las Partidas Y Provincias Del Mundo*, while describing the native settlement of Yaharo (present-day Dibulla, Colombia).
[src:avocado/avocado] The first detailed account that unequivocally describes the avocado was given by Gonzalo Fernández de Oviedo y Valdés in his work *Sumario de la natural historia de las Indias* in 1526, while holding administrative Spanish colonial duties in Santo Domingo and visiting Castilla de Oro.
[src:avocado/avocado] The first written record in English of the use of the word 'avocado' was by Hans Sloane, who coined the term, in a 1696 index of Jamaican plants.
[src:avocado/avocado] The word *avocado* comes from the Spanish *aguacate*, which derives from the Nahuatl (Mexican) word *āhuacatl* [aːˈwakat͡ɬ], which goes back to the proto-Aztecan **pa:wa*.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Molina's Nahuatl dictionary "auacatl" is given also as the translation for *compañón* "testicle", and this has been taken up in popular culture where a frequent claim is that testicle was the word's original meaning.
[src:avocado/avocado] This is not the case, as the original meaning can be reconstructed as "avocado" – rather the word seems to have been used in Nahuatl as a euphemism for "testicle".
[src:avocado/avocado] The modern English name comes from a rendering of the Spanish *aguacate* as *avogato*.
[src:avocado/avocado] The earliest known written use in English is attested from 1697 as *avogato pear*, later *avocado pear* (due to its shape), a term sometimes corrupted to *alligator pear*.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Central American, Caribbean Spanish-speaking countries, and Spain it is known by the Mexican Spanish name *aguacate*, while South American Spanish-speaking countries Argentina, Chile, Perú and Uruguay use a Quechua-derived word, *palta*.
[src:avocado/avocado] The Nahuatl *āhuacatl* can be compounded with other words, as in *ahuacamolli*, meaning avocado soup or sauce, from which the Spanish word *guacamole* derives.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Trinidad and Tobago, it is known as 'Zaboca', which is derived from the French Creole, 'l'avocat'.
[src:avocado/avocado] In the United Kingdom the term *avocado pear*, applied when avocados first became commonly available in the 1960s, is sometimes used.
[src:avocado/avocado] Originating as a diminutive in Australian English, a clipped form, *avo*, has since become a common colloquialism in South Africa and the United Kingdom.
[src:avocado/avocado] It is known as "butter fruit" in parts of India and Hong Kong.
[src:avocado/avocado] Domestication, leading to genetically distinct cultivars, is traditionally believed to have originated in the Tehuacan Valley in the state of Puebla, Mexico.
[src:avocado/avocado] However, archaeological findings suggest a much earlier human interaction with the fruit.
[src:avocado/avocado] The oldest known avocado remains were discovered at Huaca Prieta, a preceramic site on the northern coast of Peru, where humans were consuming avocados as early as 10,500 years ago.
[src:avocado/avocado] This predates other known evidence, such as avocado pits found in Coxcatlan Cave, dating from around 9,000 to 10,000 years ago, which was previously thought to be the oldest discovery of an avocado pit.
[src:avocado/avocado] Other caves in the Tehuacan Valley from around the same time period also show early evidence for the presence and consumption of avocado.
[src:avocado/avocado] The Guatemalan and Mexican landraces originated in the highlands of those countries, while the West Indian landrace is a lowland variety that ranges from Guatemala, Costa Rica, Colombia, Ecuador to Peru, achieving a wide range through human agency before the arrival of the Europeans.
[src:avocado/avocado] The three separate landraces were most likely to have already intermingled in pre-Columbian America and were described in the Florentine Codex.
[src:avocado/avocado] As a result of artificial selection, the fruit and correspondingly the seeds of cultivated avocados became considerably larger relative to their earlier wild forebears millennia before the Columbian exchange.
[src:avocado/avocado] The earliest residents of northern coastal Peru were living in temporary camps in an ancient wetland and eating avocados, along with chilies, mollusks, sharks, birds, and sea lions.
[src:avocado/avocado] There is additional evidence for avocado use at Norte Chico civilization sites in Peru at Caballo Muerto in Peru from around 3,800 to 4,500 years ago.
[src:avocado/avocado] The avocado tree has a long history of cultivation in Central and South America, now known to be much earlier than previously thought.
[src:avocado/avocado] A water jar shaped like an avocado, dating to AD 900, was discovered in the pre-Inca city of Chan Chan.
[src:avocado/avocado] The plant was introduced to Spain in 1601, Indonesia around 1750, Mauritius in 1780, Brazil in 1809, the United States mainland in 1825, South Africa and Australia in the late 19th century, and the Ottoman Empire in 1908.
[src:avocado/avocado] In the United States, the avocado was introduced to Florida and Hawaii in 1833 and in California in 1856.
[src:avocado/avocado] The name *avocado* has been used in English since at least 1764, with minor spelling variants such as *avogato* attested even earlier.
[src:avocado/avocado] As a subtropical species, avocados need a climate without frost and with little wind.
[src:avocado/avocado] High winds reduce the humidity, dehydrate the flowers, and affect pollination.
[src:avocado/avocado] When even a mild frost occurs, premature fruit drop may occur; although the 'Hass' cultivar can tolerate temperatures down to −1°C.
[src:avocado/avocado] Several cold-hardy varieties are planted in the region of Gainesville, Florida, which survive temperatures as low as −6.5 °C (20 °F) with only minor leaf damage.
[src:avocado/avocado] The trees also need well-aerated soils, ideally more than 1 m deep.
[src:avocado/avocado] However, Guatemalan varieties such as "MacArthur", "Rincon", or "Nabal" can withstand temperatures down to −1.6 °C (29 °F).
[src:avocado/avocado] However, the amount of water needed depends on where it is grown; for example, in the main avocado-growing region of Chile, about 320 L (85 US gal; 70 imp gal) of applied water are needed to grow one avocado (1,280 L/kg [153 US gal/lb; 128 imp gal/lb]).
[src:avocado/avocado] Increasing demand and production of avocados may cause water shortages in some avocado production areas, such as the Mexican state of Michoacán.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados may also cause environmental and socioeconomic impacts in major production areas, illegal deforestation, and water disputes.
[src:avocado/avocado] Water requirements for growing avocados are three times higher than for apples, and 18 times higher than for tomatoes.
[src:avocado/avocado] Commercial orchards produce an average of seven tonnes per hectare each year, with some orchards achieving 20 tonnes per hectare.
[src:avocado/avocado] Biennial bearing can be a problem, with heavy crops in one year being followed by poor yields the next.
[src:avocado/avocado] Like the banana, the avocado is a climacteric fruit, which matures on the tree, but ripens off the tree.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados used in commerce are picked hard and green and kept in coolers at 3.3 to 5.6 °C (37.9 to 42.1 °F) until they reach their final destination.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados must be mature to ripen properly.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados that fall off the tree ripen on the ground.
[src:avocado/avocado] Generally, the fruit is picked once it reaches maturity; Mexican growers pick 'Hass' avocados when they have more than 23% dry matter, and other producing countries have similar standards.
[src:avocado/avocado] Once picked, avocados ripen in one to two weeks (depending on the cultivar) at room temperature (faster if stored with other fruits such as apples or bananas, because of the influence of ethylene gas).
[src:avocado/avocado] Some supermarkets sell ripened avocados which have been treated with synthetic ethylene to hasten ripening.
[src:avocado/avocado] In some cases, avocados can be left on the tree for several months, which is an advantage to commercial growers who seek the greatest return for their crop, but if the fruit remains unpicked for too long, it falls to the ground.
[src:avocado/avocado] Cold storage is sometimes used to maximize productivity, but if the temperature is too low, it can have a negative impact on the quality of the fruit, resulting in unseemly spots on the skin of the fruit, and an interior which is discolored, too fibrous, and putrid.
[src:avocado/avocado] The species is only partially able to self-pollinate because of dichogamy in its flowering.
[src:avocado/avocado] This limitation, added to the long juvenile period, makes the species difficult to breed.
[src:avocado/avocado] Most cultivars are propagated by grafting, having originated from random seedling plants or minor mutations derived from cultivars.
[src:avocado/avocado] Modern breeding programs tend to use isolation plots where the chances of cross-pollination are reduced.
[src:avocado/avocado] That is the case for programs at the University of California, Riverside, as well as the Volcani Centre and the Instituto de Investigaciones Agropecuarias in Chile.
[src:avocado/avocado] The avocado is unusual in that the timing of the male and female flower phases differs among cultivars.
[src:avocado/avocado] A-cultivar flowers open as female on the morning of the first day and close in late morning or early afternoon.
[src:avocado/avocado] Then they open as male in the afternoon of the second day.
[src:avocado/avocado] B varieties open as female on the afternoon of the first day, close in late afternoon and reopen as male the following morning.
[src:avocado/avocado] Certain cultivars, such as the 'Hass', have a tendency to bear well only in alternate years.
[src:avocado/avocado] After a season with a low yield, due to factors such as cold (which the avocado does not tolerate well), the trees tend to produce abundantly the next season.
[src:avocado/avocado] In addition, due to environmental circumstances during some years, seedless avocados may appear on the trees.
[src:avocado/avocado] Known in the avocado industry as "cukes", they are usually discarded commercially due to their small size.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados can be propagated by seed, taking roughly four to six years to bear fruit, although in some cases seedlings can take 10 years to come into bearing.
[src:avocado/avocado] The offspring is unlikely to be identical to the parent cultivar in fruit quality.
[src:avocado/avocado] Prime quality varieties are therefore propagated by grafting to rootstocks that are propagated by seed (seedling rootstocks) or by layering (clonal rootstocks).
[src:avocado/avocado] After about a year of growing in a greenhouse, the young rootstocks are ready to be grafted.
[src:avocado/avocado] Terminal and lateral grafting is normally used.
[src:avocado/avocado] The scion cultivar grows for another 6–12 months before the tree is ready to be sold.
[src:avocado/avocado] Clonal rootstocks are selected for tolerance of specific soil and disease conditions, such as poor soil aeration or resistance to the soil-borne disease (root rot) caused by *Phytophthora cinnamomi*.
[src:avocado/avocado] Advances in cloning techniques that can produce up to 500 new plants from a single millimetre of tree cutting have the potential to increase the availability of rootstocks.
[src:avocado/avocado] Commercial avocado production is limited to a small fraction of the vast genetic diversity in the species.
[src:avocado/avocado] Conservation of this genetic diversity has relied largely on field collection, as avocado seeds often do not survive storage in seed banks.
[src:avocado/avocado] This is problematic, as field preservation of living cultivars is expensive, and habitat loss threatens wild cultivars.
[src:avocado/avocado] More recently, an alternate method of conservation has been developed based on cryopreservation of avocado somatic embryos with reliable methods for somatic embryogenesis and reconstitution into living trees.
[src:avocado/avocado] The avocado tree can be grown domestically and used as a decorative houseplant.
[src:avocado/avocado] The pit germinates in normal soil conditions or partially submerged in a small glass (or container) of water.
[src:avocado/avocado] In the latter method, the pit sprouts in four to six weeks, at which time it is planted in standard houseplant potting soil.
[src:avocado/avocado] The plant normally grows large enough to be prunable; it does not bear fruit unless it has ample sunlight.
[src:avocado/avocado] Home gardeners can graft a branch from a fruit-bearing plant to speed maturity, which typically takes four to six years to bear fruit.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado trees are vulnerable to bacterial, viral, fungal, and nutritional diseases (excesses and deficiencies of key minerals).
[src:avocado/avocado] Disease can affect all parts of the plant, causing spotting, rotting, cankers, pitting, and discoloration.
[src:avocado/avocado] The pyriform scale insect (*Protopulvinaria pyriformis*) is known from Australia, South Africa, Israel, Italy, France, Spain, Cuba, Florida, and Peru.
[src:avocado/avocado] It is normally found on avocado, and in Peru it is said to be the worst insect pest of the fruit.
[src:avocado/avocado] Certain cultivars of avocado seem more susceptible to attack by the scale than others.
[src:avocado/avocado] In 2024, world production of avocados was 11.2 million tonnes, led by Mexico with 25% of the total (table).
[src:avocado/avocado] Other significant producers were Colombia, Dominican Republic, Peru, and Indonesia.
[src:avocado/avocado] A 2024 market analysis indicated that avocado exports will increase over the next five years with as many as 30 countries producing avocados, possibly becoming the world's most traded fruit by 2030.
[src:avocado/avocado] Some people have allergic reactions to avocado.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado leaves, bark, skin, or pit are documented to be harmful to animals; cats, dogs, cattle, goats, rabbits, rats, guinea pigs, birds, fish, and horses can be severely harmed or even killed when they consume them.
[src:avocado/avocado] The avocado fruit is poisonous to some birds, and the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (ASPCA) lists it as toxic to horses.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado leaves contain a toxic fatty acid derivative, persin, which in sufficient quantity can cause colic in horses and without veterinary treatment, death.
[src:avocado/avocado] The symptoms include gastrointestinal irritation, vomiting, diarrhea, respiratory distress, congestion, fluid accumulation around the tissues of the heart, and even death.
[src:avocado/avocado] Birds also seem to be particularly sensitive to this toxic compound.
[src:avocado/avocado] The leaves of the Guatemalan variety of *P. americana* are toxic to goats, sheep, and horses.
[src:avocado/avocado] Raw avocado flesh is 73% water, 15% fat, 9% carbohydrates, and 2% protein (table).
[src:avocado/avocado] In a 100-gram reference amount, avocado supplies 670 kilojoules (160 kilocalories), and is a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of several B vitamins (such as 28% DV in pantothenic acid) and vitamin K (20% DV), with moderate contents (10–19% DV) of vitamin C, vitamin E, and potassium.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados also contain phytosterols and carotenoids, such as lutein and zeaxanthin.
[src:avocado/avocado] Although costly to produce, nutrient-rich avocado oil has a multitude of uses for salads or cooking and in cosmetics and soap products.
[src:avocado/avocado] Reviews of clinical research found that avocado consumption may lower blood levels of low-density lipoprotein and total cholesterol, two biomarkers of cardiovascular disease.
[src:avocado/avocado] The fruit of horticultural cultivars has a markedly higher fat content than most other fruit, mostly monounsaturated fat, and as such serves as an important staple in the diet of consumers who have limited access to other fatty foods (high-fat meats and fish, dairy products).
[src:avocado/avocado] Having a high smoke point, avocado oil is expensive compared to common salad and cooking oils, and is mostly used for salads or dips.
[src:avocado/avocado] A ripe avocado yields to gentle pressure when held in the palm of the hand and squeezed.
[src:avocado/avocado] The flesh is prone to enzymatic browning, quickly turning brown after exposure to air.
[src:avocado/avocado] To prevent this, lime or lemon juice can be added to avocados after peeling.
[src:avocado/avocado] The fruit is not sweet, but distinctly and subtly flavored, with smooth texture.
[src:avocado/avocado] It is used in both savory and sweet dishes, though in many countries not for both.
[src:avocado/avocado] The avocado is common in vegetarian cuisine as a substitute for meats in sandwiches and salads because of its high fat content.
[src:avocado/avocado] Generally, avocado is served raw, though some cultivars, including the common 'Hass', can be cooked for a short time without becoming bitter.
[src:avocado/avocado] The flesh of some avocados may be rendered inedible by heat.
[src:avocado/avocado] Prolonged cooking induces this chemical reaction in all cultivars.
[src:avocado/avocado] It is used as the base for the Mexican dip known as guacamole, as well as a spread on corn tortillas or toast, served with spices.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado is a primary ingredient in avocado soup.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado slices are frequently added to hamburgers and *tortas* and is a key ingredient in California rolls and other *makizushi* ("maki", or rolled sushi).
[src:avocado/avocado] When trying to serve the avocado fruit by cutting into it, people sometimes cut their hand severely.
[src:avocado/avocado] The term 'avocado hand' has been coined for this injury.
[src:avocado/avocado] The prevalence of these injuries increased in the United States between 1998 and 2017 as avocado consumption increased.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Mexico and Central America, avocados are served mixed with white rice, in soups, salads, or on the side of chicken and meat.
[src:avocado/avocado] They are also commonly added to *pozole*.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Peru, they are consumed with *tequeños* as mayonnaise, served as a side dish with *parrillas*, used in salads and sandwiches, or as a whole dish when filled with tuna, shrimp, or chicken.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Chile, it is used as a puree-like sauce with chicken, hamburgers, and hot dogs; and in slices for celery or lettuce salads.
[src:avocado/avocado] The Chilean version of Caesar salad contains large slices of mature avocado.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocado forms the base of *guasacaca*, a sauce found in Venezuela and the Dominican Republic.
[src:avocado/avocado] Avocados in savory dishes, often seen as exotic, are a relative novelty in Portuguese-speaking countries, such as Brazil, where the traditional preparation is mashed with sugar and lime, and eaten as a dessert or snack.
[src:avocado/avocado] In the Philippines (where avocados were introduced from Mexico since before the 1700s), Brazil, Indonesia, Vietnam, and southern India (especially the coastal Kerala, Tamil Nadu and Karnataka region), avocados are frequently used for milkshakes and occasionally added to ice cream and other desserts.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Brazil, the Philippines Vietnam, and Indonesia, a dessert drink is made with sugar, milk or water, and pureed avocado.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Morocco, a similar chilled avocado and milk drink is sweetened with confectioner's sugar and flavored with a touch of orange flower water.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Ethiopia, avocados are made into juice by mixing them with sugar and milk or water, usually served with Vimto and a slice of lemon.
[src:avocado/avocado] It is also common to serve layered multiple fruit juices in a glass (locally called *Spris*) made of avocados, mangoes, bananas, guavas, and papayas.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Kenya and Nigeria, the avocado is often eaten as a fruit alone or mixed with other fruits in a fruit salad, or as part of a vegetable salad.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Ghana, they are often eaten alone on sliced bread as a sandwich.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Sri Lanka, their well-ripened flesh, thoroughly mashed or pureed with milk and *kitul* treacle (a liquid jaggery made from the sap of the inflorescence of jaggery palms), is a common dessert.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Haiti, they are often consumed with cassava or regular bread for breakfast.
[src:avocado/avocado] In the United Kingdom, the avocado became available during the 1960s when introduced by Sainsbury's under the name 'avocado pear'.
[src:avocado/avocado] Much of the success of avocados in the UK is attributed to a long-running promotional campaign initiated by South African growers in 1995.
[src:avocado/avocado] In Australia and New Zealand, avocados are commonly served on sandwiches, sushi, toast, or with chicken.
[src:avocado/avocado] In addition to the fruit, the leaves of Mexican avocados (*Persea americana* var.
[src:avocado/avocado] *drymifolia*) are used in some cuisines as a spice, with a flavor somewhat reminiscent of anise.
[src:avocado/avocado] They are sold both dried and fresh, toasted before use, and either crumbled or used whole, commonly in bean dishes.
